Patient was encouraged to undergo Serogroup B Meningococcal Vaccination per CDC recommendation following two confirmed cases of Meningitis B at the University. After a week post vaccination characterized by general malaise (chills early, then predominantly tiredness), in the PM of Friday Dec 8 the patient suffered a series of Generalized Tonic-Clonic seizures in her dorm, accompanied by disorientation, confusion and possibly/eventually unconsciousness. Leading to an 9-1-1 call, ambulance transport to local hospital then immediately to the ER, where she was hospitalized in the Dept. of Neurology until discharge 4 days later.
LAB_DATA: A complete workup for suspected CNS disease followed immediately, including -imaging (MRI, CT): normal; - EEG, slowed but recovering, consistent with recovery from GTC seizure(s) - lumbar puncture and spinal fluid analysis: primarily lymphocytic encephalitis, else normal - later followed by serology for known infectious diseases (Herpes Simplex, Var. Zoster, Trep. pallidum, Cryptocc, others?): all negative
OTHER_MEDS: insulin, short-acting, multi-dose, daily; insulin, long-acting, 1/d

As a condition of my employment every new employee is required to get a Influenza shot before they can start work. Well. I this is what I thought I got until I was diagnosed with Shingles in the ear in Dec. 2017. Up to this point, about two weeks to 30 days I got a rash on my stomach. I thought maybe it was something I was allergic to so I just bought antifungal cream from the store. The second rash about maybe two a month later showed up on my chest below my collar bone but above my chest. This lasted a while and then the third rash sometime in Sept. 2017 on the back of my neck around my hair line. When I look at my chart it shows that I had a varicella zoster vaccination instead of a influenza vaccination. So now it is all adding up. Just looking back on the symptoms; rashes, dizzy spells, headaches, and muscle aches I can conclude that I've had Shingles for some time now. It just progressed until it ended. The second vaccination I got in Nov. I'm not sure if that was the wrong vaccination or not. I have requested my records. Well, due to having Shingles, the pain and inflammation my nerves on my right side of my face are paralyzed. I believe I am sick because I was administered the wrong vaccination., I was not scheduled to have a varicella zoster shot it was supposed to be the influenza shot. Considering I've never had chicken pox before this shot should not have been administered without my consent. I was told I was getting an influenza. Now I'm not feeling well and my face on one side does not work because I was given the wrong vaccination in error.
LAB_DATA: I have had a number of test done to rule out other causes. So far my test results from my lab work have come back negative. So I don't think its a coincidence that I had a varicella zoster vaccination now I have Shingles.

This literature marketed report was received from the authors of the published article. A 4-year-old boy presented with a 1-month history of three soft, pruritic, subcutaneous, 1-cm mobile nodules on the anterior left and right thighs with overlying hypopigmentation, excoriated dermatitis, and moderate xerosis. The patient had a history of persistent cervical lymphadenopathy of the right anterior and lateral neck, eczema on the flanks and upper buttock, and keratosis pilaris on the posterior bilateral arms. Viral studies were unremarkable except for detectible immunoglobulin G antibodies to Epstein–Barr virus indicating a previous infection. The patient's family first observed the nodules after he had received a hepatitis A vaccine (manufacturer unknown) in the left thigh 1 month before. The patient received six vaccinations: three doses of the diphtheria, tetanus, pertussis, polio vaccine – Haemophilus influenzae type b conjugate vaccine and three doses of the pneumococcal vaccine. There was no record of where on the patient these vaccines were administered. His scheduled vaccination program was continued after he and his family moved. A punch biopsy of a nodule on the left anterior thigh was performed for histopathologic examination. A punch biopsy specimen demonstrated lobular panniculitis with a dense infiltrate composed of lymphocytes, histiocytes, plasma cells, numerous eosinophils, and clusters of dendritic Langerhans cells. Stains for microorganisms were unrevealing. The patient underwent patch testing and at 96 hours had a 2+ positive reaction to 2.0% aluminum chloride hexahydrate. In the months after, the patient developed diffuse hypopigmented patches on his trunk and overlying the thigh nodules. The patient was diagnosed with aluminum hypersensitivity. The outcome of events was unknown. The authors considered the events to be related to aluminium salts used as adjuvants in vaccines, including hepatitis A vaccine (manufacturer unknown).
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Eczema (on the flanks and upper buttock); Epstein-Barr virus infection; Keratosis pilaris (on the posterior bilateral arms); Lymphadenopathy cervical (right anterior and lateral neck)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient had a pre-syncopal event following the event. He felt pale and nauseous; dizzy. Did not pass out. 3-4 days later developed a very dry rash on cheeks of face bilaterally. I do not think the rash is related to the immunization. No hives.

Patient tolerated flu injection well, she was talkative with mom and was able to out of the room unassisted. Mom had to stop at our front desk for future scheduling, a that time patient was found to be sitting in the waiting room chair, slumped back and pale. Nursing staff was readily available to assist patient and mother (patient was still in chair and did not fall nor slip off), a doctor was called out to the waiting room help to assess the patient as well. Pt was instructed to lean forward, take deep breaths, and a cool compress was applied to the nape of her neck. Her BP was checked. Orange juice was provided to the patient as well. Patient felt well enough to walk back to the office room where she was monitored and re-assessed by her doctor. Her BP and pulse was continuously monitored, OJ was provided to drink, and a cool compress was also applied to her forehead. Patient stayed with mother in office room for several minutes. Prior to discharge, pt's doctor re-assessed patient and discharged her. The office placed a follow up call with mother the net day, she was very appreciative of the call. Patient was doing well the following day with no adverse symptoms reported. Mom explained that she forgot too mention to staff that patient had fainted when she was 11 years old after receiving the flu vaccine. This has been noted in the chart for future reference of staff and provider.
HISTORY: None. After adverse effect to vaccination, mom mentioned that patient experienced a similar  syncopal episode when she received the flu vaccine when she was 11 years old.
PRIOR_VAX: mom mentioned post-injection reaction that patient had a similar syncopal episode after receiving the flu vaccination.

Patient reported tenderness and pain at site of injection which radiated down the right arm and up to the shoulder and neck. Pain is not sharp and there is no numbness or tingling. Patient can raise arm slightly. The injection site was not red or swollen. Patient was able to work today at her job.

Thirty minutes post vaccination the employee called to report that her throat was scratchy and tight. I advised her to come to the ER to be evaluated for anaphylactic reaction to the vaccines. She also reported a warm feeling that went up her neck when she received the Hepatitis vaccination. She was seen in the ER and given DECADRON 10mg IM x1 injection, and Rx for prednisone 20mg 3 tabs by mouth x5 days, and PEPCID 20mg 1 every 12hours daily x10 days.
Had fever up to 104, widespread scattered  rash-no treatment.
Onset of generalized weakness/ whole body went limp/ febrile/ change of overall color with pallor and stopped breathing/ was given CPR and paramedics were called/ baby was then brought to ER.

Felt the flu shot was given really high in my shoulder. After, experienced more pain than usual, pain increased each day and I experienced limited mobility and increased weakness. On day 4 went to doctor and started ibuprofen for inflammation. Pain still got worse after that. Hard to even put a shirt on. On day 10, went back to the doctor and they got an MRI later in the day. MRI showed inflammation and fluid build-up so started on a steroid. Shoulder still is hurting even on the steroids and having some weakness and limited mobility. Now waiting to see if the pain goes away when steroid is done. Doctor suggested it may be painful/inflamed due to the shot being given too high and going through the muscle and into the bursa sac. Pain is most severe when shoulder is reached above the head or moved laterally behind or across body.

I was administered Hepatitis A Vaccine by shot in my right arm, momentarily afterward there were symptoms of nausea, fatigue, and fainting. I had to have immediate stitches given due to head injury. Nausea and fatigue symptoms lasted for a couple days.

WITHIN 24 HOURS AFTER RECEIVING THE ABOVE IMMUNIZATIONS PATIENT REPORTED FLU LIKE SIGNS AND SYMPTOMS, SORE TONGUE, SORE THROAT, BURNING LIPS, BURNING THROAT, JOINT PAIN, CHILLS, FATIGUE, FEVER, AND HEADACHE.
Rigors, muscle aches 102 temp.

Severe pain in left shoulder near injection site (high on outer back part of arm) that started within a day of administration. Pain is dull and constant and has progressively gotten worse over the past month plus. Reaching across and above my body with my left arm causes excruciating pain and disrupts my daily activities including work, exercise, sleep and showering/ getting dressed. I was treated for bursitis with a 6-day steroid regimen (Prednisone 5 MG) after a follow up appt with her on 12/5/17. One day 2, the pain ceased but it came back even worse before I had finished the doses. Went back to see Dr.  on 12/11/17 and she told me to "schedule ib profen" 3 times a day for 2 weeks to reduce the inflammation and said it was likely tendonitis. I have been taking the ib profen routinely for pain but it has not helped. The pain has now been going on for almost 2 months.
LAB_DATA: No X-rays or tests but 2 Dr appts since the adverse reaction on 12/5 and 12/11/17.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Per patient report: My arm was extremely painful that night with swelling about 6 inches around the shot site was hard to sleep and had to put cold packs on it. The next day it was swollen on the outside of the arm down to the elbow. The 3rd day it was swollen on the bicep with about a 1/4 inch raise. Then heart palpitations, fluttering happened throughout the day, sometimes for 14 seconds or longer. The 4th day the swelling disappeared and so did the palpitations. Myalgia, erythema multiform, palpitations and swelling 6 inches around injection site.
HISTORY: Multiple medication allergies - Codeine (unknown reaction), niacin (unknown), glipizide (flushing, pruritus, nausea), BACTRIM (unknown), rifampin (unknown), lisinopril (flushing, hypertension, leg swelling with one manufacturer - ok with another one)

This case involves a female patient (age not reported), who was vaccinated once with 0.5 ml HINI INFLUENZA VACCINE via intramuscular route (batch number: UP013AA; expiry date: 15-SEP-2010, dose in series and site of administration not reported) on 29-Oct-2009. On an unknown date, few weeks following the vaccination, patient developed "progression of symptoms, numbness face and arms, blood pressure 200/100, fainted twice" seen in ER (emergency room) and diagnosed with H1N1 viral syndrome. On an unknown date, patient got hospitalized. It was also a case of suspected vaccination failure. Other lab test was not reported. Corrective treatment was not reported. On an unknown date, patient recovered from the events. No information reported on hospital discharge. Documents held by sender: none. This is a spontaneous report from a Pfizer-sponsored program, received from a contactable consumer (reporting for herself). A 78-year-old female patient started to receive PREVNAR 13 (NDC number: 00005-1971-05), via an unspecified route of administration at a single dose in the right arm as she was 78 and told needed a pneumonia shot and FLUZONE HD; (NDC number: 49281-0401-65), via an unspecified route of administration at unknown dose and frequency in the left arm to prevent colds and flu both given on 21Nov2017. Medical history included bronchitis and ongoing glaucoma. The patient commented that she keeps shrinking. Concomitant medication included ongoing latanoprost, patient was taking for 4-5 years for glaucoma slow down. On 22Nov2017 (reported as next day after receiving the vaccine), the patient reported that she was not able to move her arm, not able to lift anything, pain in arm and in a lot of pain. The patient tried a heating pad and nothing is working. It was further reported that the patient got her flu shot in her left arm in the normal spot and her PREVNAR 13 was in the right arm. The patient feels the bandage is higher on the right arm and commented that she feels like maybe with PREVNAR 13 hit the bone as the bandage was not normally where she had been given a shot. Both vaccine was given on the same day however her left arm was fine. The patient reported that pain was excruciating during the shot. The soreness and not able to move her right arm started next day after receiving the vaccine which the patient reported most painful at night. The patient also reported that her range of motion is about 45 degrees, it still hurts to put on a coat and can't put on her sweater. The pain is a dull when her arm is hanging down by her side and sharper if she lifts or moves it. The patient also reported that she got possible bronchitis, but not diagnosed, and coughing. The patient has had bronchitis before and that is what it felt like as the patient reported. The outcome of the events was unknown. The symptoms from the cough and what felt like bronchitis had resolved on unspecified date. Information on the batch number/ expiry date has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Email received 12/29/17 from patient: Sent: Friday, December 29, 2017 1:25 PM Subject: flu vaccine reaction I heard you may be the person to talk to? I had a fairly severe reaction to my flu shot I received this year. I filled out an EMS report and left a message for employee health to call me but never heard back from them. Within an hour of my flu shot I developed significant blurred vision and confusion and went on to develop some intense joint pain with fatigue later that day and into the night. I normally do not have neurological problems and I have perfect vision at baseline. My questions are as follows: 1. What is the lot number of the flu vaccination I received and what are the specific additives? 2. Are there other people who received the flu vaccination this year that had adverse side effects similar to myself? 3. Who is responsible for reporting this adverse reaction to the CDC or other pertinent agencies? 4. What are the recommendations for future flu shots based on my reaction to this one? Thank you for your time and attention to this matter. Follow up email received 1/3/18: I never had any tests or ER visits done.  I did fill out an SAS report and also contacted my primary care providers office to report event in case they wanted to see me.  The best I can tell, I am recovered with the exception that I've been experiencing more joint pain than I can recall in the past but I'm not sure if that is related or just coincidence.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is exchange student. Her host mother texted me a photo of patient's arm about 48 hours after vaccination. The photo showed 2 quarter sized circular patches of skin on her anterior forearm just above her antecubital area. Patient told her host mother that these patches were "itchy" and that her arm was achy. The vaccine was given in her left deltoid muscle several inches away from reddened area. Patient told her host mother that this started about 8 hours after the vaccine was given and skin was itchy. The reddened patches had not changed in size in last 24 hours per client. She also described her arm as "achy." Reviewed routine side effects with her host mom which includes sore muscle and instructed that ibuprofen or acetaminophen could help with achiness. Also recommended cool compress to arm. Suggested marking edges of reddened area with waterproof marker to determine if reddened area was increasing in size. Instructed to seek medical attention if skin worsening or any additional reddened area appears.
Client was given a pediatric Hepatitis A vaccine and should have been given an adult Hepatitis A vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Please note that I am not aware if this was Men B BEXSERO OR Men B TRUMENBA; On December 23rd in the evening my son started to feel nauseated with a headache and backache. I gave him 600 mg of Ibuprofen at about 1830. By 1900 his temp was 101.2 F and he was stating he couldn't feel his feet and left arm. This was a Holiday weekend, and I don't have confidence in my designated ER. I read the vaccine info sheet. I hydrated him and administered TYLENOL as I was sponging him with tepid water. His temp continued to climb to 101.8 over the next few hours. My plan was to bring him to the ER if his temp reached 102 despite the cooling measures. By about 2300 his temp began to slowly drop and he was feeling better. Over the next day he was complaining of pain under his armpit. He continued taking Ibuprofen 400 mg every 6 hours for the next several days as he continued with a temperature. The site of the injection remained red and swollen for about 3 days. His temp was normal after 4 days. On the 3rd day we noted that he had a considerable amount of fluid (presumably lymph) under his left arm. It extended from his armpit down his side approx 8 inches, and anterior posterior about 6 inches. This fluid has slowly been presumably reabsorbing, and is now just present in his armpit. This was the most distressing part for him as it was quite uncomfortable. We described it to people as if he had a Jello mold stuck on his side. As you would touch it his whole under arm would jiggle. It was quite obvious on a 6'3" 160 pound swimmer athlete. He finally felt "back to Normal" after approx. 5 days post vaccination. He had no other complaints besides the arm pain, fever, nausea, headache, back pain.
OTHER_MEDS: albuterol prn for exercise induced asthma

Additional information was provided. This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of systemic lupus erythematosus in a 17-year-old female who was vaccinated with MENVEO (GlaxoSmithKline). The patient was a previously healthy female. Her immunizations were up to date. The patient had no history of vaccine reactions, allergic reactions, recent travel, known sick contacts, animal exposure, or significant outdoor activity. She did not take any medications regularly. No information on family history was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received MENVEO (administration route and site unspecified; dosages unknown; batch number not provided). On an unspecified date, an evening after the vaccination, the patient began to feel ill. 5 days prior to the emergency department (ED) visit, the patient developed a progressive, erythematous, non-pruritic, non-painful facial rash. Prior to ED presentation, the patient received 2 days of cefadroxil and there was no improvement in her symptoms. Review of systems was positive only for mild right-sided neck pain. 15 days after receiving the vaccine, the patient presented to ED with 14 days of fever and fatigue. Initial vital signs included a blood pressure of 110/61 mmHg, heart rate of 102 bpm, respiratory rate of 20, an oxygen saturation of 97% and a temporal temperature of 102.4 degree F (39.1 deg. C). She was an ill appearing female with a non-blanching, erythematous maculopapular facial rash, including the right periorbital region and bilateral upper cheeks, with extension to the right ear. The rash was associated with mild right periorbital swelling, as well as perioral dermatitis and dry, chapped lips. She had a painless ulceration of the hard palate. Her first, second, and third fingertips revealed non-painful, purpuric lesions bilaterally. Neck exam was significant for palpable right posterior cervical chain lymphadenopathy without meningismus. The remainder of her exam was unremarkable. Complete blood count (CBC) revealed pancytopenia. The white blood cells (WBC) was 2.8 (neutrophils 48% with 13% bands; there were 35% lymphocytes and 4% monocytes); the HgB was 10.2 and the platelets were 48,000 (normal values not provided). The D-dimer and erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) were elevated at 1.38 and 40, respectively. Urinalysis showed protein, blood, and leukocytes. All other initial labs were unremarkable, electrocardiogram (EKG) and chest x-ray (CXR) were normal. Computed tomography (CT) of the head and neck revealed diffuse bilateral lymphadenopathy. The patient was admitted to the Medical intensive care unit (ICU). On Day 2, despite empiric antibiotic therapy, the patient's CBC demonstrated worsening pancytopenia, with WBC 1.7. Prednisone was started and her pancytopenia began to resolve. All cultures were negative and antibiotics were discontinued on Day 5. On Day 7 she was started on the immunosuppressant CELLCEPT; her fever and rash improved. Serological testing was positive for SLE (antinuclear antibodies titer of 1:320 and anti-double-stranded deoxyribonucleic acid titer of 1:640). On Day 9, the patient was discharged with prednisone and mycophenolate and PLAQUENIL. At one-month follow up, the patient was doing well. This case has been considered serious due to hospitalisation. The authors commented, 'In our case, the extreme proximity of the vaccination to the clinical symptoms, and the pathognomonic serologic findings argues in favour of a cause and effect relationship between the vaccine and classical SLE'. The author stated, 'Our case highlights the importance of inquiring about recent vaccinations in any patient presenting with the unexplained onset of symptoms typical of autoimmune disease'.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of vaccination failure in a 80-year-old female patient who received Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season. Co-suspect products included BREO ELLIPTA unknown for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Concurrent medical conditions included heart disorder, tiredness (normally tired) and pneumonia (1 year before reporting date). Concomitant products included PROAIR. In October 2017, the patient received Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season. On an unknown date, the patient started BREO ELLIPTA 1 puff(s) once daily. On 15th December 2017, less than a year after receiving Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season and BREO ELLIPTA, the patient experienced feeling unwell. In December 2017, the patient experienced condition aggravated and tiredness. On 17th December 2017, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and influenza. The patient was treated with ondansetron hydrochloride and oseltamivir. Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season was continued with no change. BREO ELLIPTA was continued with no change. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, condition aggravated and tiredness were unknown and the outcome of the influenza and feeling unwell were recovering/resolving. The reporter considered the vaccination failure, influenza, feeling unwell, condition aggravated and tiredness to be unrelated to Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season and BREO ELLIPTA. Additional details were reported as follows: The patient had been on BREO ELLIPTA for about a year, it was been between 6 months to a year. She stated that she also got a flu shot in late October or early November at a Pharmacy. The patient did not know the manufacturer of the flu vaccine. The patient noted before last Friday she was not feeling good and tired, but was always tired. On Saturday the patient felt worse and then on Sunday she went to an outpatient care and they diagnosed her with the flu. This case was considered as suspected vaccination failure case since the laboratory test for influenza was unknown. The patient noted she almost completed the medications. The reporter does not relate any of these events to the medications. She noted she took a lot of medications on routine, but did not want to provide those. The healthcare professional declined for information and does not want him contacted. The patient denied permission to contact their physician.
CUR_ILL: Cardiac disorder; Fatigue, normally tired; Pneumonia, 1 year before reporting date

I received a flu shot in November at pharmacy. I pulled my sleeve up as high as I've ever had to in the past and the pharmacist insisted it wasn't high enough. Rather than remove my shirt, I yanked on the sleeve to get it to raise higher. He proceeded to inject the flu shot extremely high and in my shoulder. The medicine burned going in and a short while later I felt a sharp pain in my shoulder. A week later when it hurt to even move the shoulder I went to an orthopedic shoulder specialist who diagnosed the pain as tendonitis/Bursitis and put me on an ice and OTC anti-inflammatory regimen. Two weeks later, when that treatment didn't work, he gave me a steroid injection. That's been two weeks now and the pain is still as bad as ever. He says I need an MRI next. I was fine before the flu shot and now I can hardly lift or move my arm due to the sharp piercing pain.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: STROKE. Patient presented with left hemiplegia and facial droop with MRI/MRA for large acute/subacute right MCA infarct. He was afebrile, normotensive, without any electrolyte derangement. He had recurrent seizure activities on 11/23 and 11/24, for which he received Keppra and fosphenytoin. He was weaned of the fosphenytoin on 11/28 and continues on Keppra. Left hospital for inpatient rehabilitation for 2 weeks. After, at home with outpatient physical and occupational therapy 3x week.
LAB_DATA: MRI/MRA - large acute/subacute right MCA infarct. (11/21/17); EEG - some slowing, no seizure activity (11/22/17); echocarciograms- did not show any abnormalities. (11/22/17, 11/24/17)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Following vaccine administration (pt had received 5 vaccines), patient turned pale and went unconscious, while seated in a chair. LOC 5 seconds. Patient briefly shook and then awoke. Pt was fasting. Symptoms spontaneously resolved. Patient received final vaccine and waited in office at least 30 min. following. No further symptoms. No hx of vaccine reactions. Upon d/c, mom reports that while unconscious, patient's entire body was shaking. Discussed further with RN's who witnessed event. No seizure activity reported.
He was talking, walking and acting normal and progressing, and after the shots he couldn't walk or speak at all....

I felt some soreness as expected in my left upper arm. That did not alarm me at all but I was shocked to see the following day that I had vaginal bleeding. I am not scheduled to have my period to the 20th of Jan so this would be very early. I have now urinated a second time and am still spotting when I pee.
CUR_ILL: Had just started feeling better from a 4 day Flu a day prior to vaccination

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At home, I blacked out and fell against a door frame. I was immediately sent to hospital. My doctors are still testing me to determine the cause of the blackout one day after receiving flu vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Gamma ray cardiology scan and stress test; Electrocardiograms.
OTHER_MEDS: ADVAIR; amlodipine 5mg; atorvastatin 20mg; fluticasone nasal spray; aspirin 81mg; vitamin D3; calcium.
HISTORY: Diabetes type II; Asthma; Bradycardia; Early Parkinson's; Coronary artery disease; slight anemia
ALLERGIES: enalapril; sulfa drugs; sulfites; Dust; Mold; Pollen; Hydrocarbon vapors.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On of diarrhea, emesis, decrease appetite to all foods and liquids about 6 hours after the vaccines. No rashes, no new wheezing and no blood in stool. No seizures.

About 10 min after the shot Patient developed hives and complained about throat pain. BENADRYL given, vomited some and half given back. Hives got slightly better but he still got throat pain. EPI PEN Jr given. Hives disappeared in 5 min and throat pain is gone. Watched Patient for another 30 min and D/C home in stable condition. In the future, all flu shots in allergy clinic.
ALLERGIES: egg white; egg yolk; sesame seed; sunflower seed; walnut

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Weakness, fever, headaches, vomiting, body aches, and fatigue for 3 days.

Adverse Event: Righ arm swelling, warmth, itching in site of immunization (Varicella) two days ago. Treatment: KEFLEX 500 mg capsule. Outcome: No evidence of ongoing infection. Provider plan: Ice, NSAID, or Acetaminophen if arm feels sore, and return precautions discussed.

She was administered the shot at 11 am and at 3 pm she started being restless and acting like she was in pain. Then at about 4 pm she started projectile vomited and struggled to breathe. The vomiting lasted for about a week and the struggling to breathe lasted about 2.5 weeks.

Pain in shoulder, limiting arm movement laterally. Two months after flu shot, went to Dr, had xray (negative), received cortisone shot in shoulder. Pain worse for 2 days, then reverted to prior condition (painful lateral movement). Still the same pain 10 weeks after flu shot.
OTHER_MEDS: tacrolimus, aziathioprine, zinc, vit D, mulit-vitamin

OTHER_MEDS: Adderall, testosterone,  Celebrex, Atripla, Effexor, Valtrex

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Complained of feeling "loopy", which he described as feeling drunk, nausea and metallic taste in mouth. Symptoms resolved on their own at 10:40 a.m. which was 23 minutes after onset.
OTHER_MEDS: 81 mg. aspirin, Vitamins b,c,d, and cinnamon

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt states that pain in arm started evening after injection was given. Pt states that she could not lift arm and that it was so painful that she went to the emergency room. Notes provided of encounter below: History of Presenting Illness: The patient is a 72 Year Old Female who presents to the ED with complaints of left arm pain that started the evening after she received a pneumonia vaccine. Patient states that she has use hot packs and TYLENOL which was effective in relieving the pain for a while. She states she has increased pain with movement. She denies any fevers, chills, nausea or vomiting. She is not having any shortness of breath or chest pain. She states she has never had an issue after receiving vaccines in the past. ED Course: 72-year-old female presents with left arm pain that started after receiving a pneumonia vaccine. She does not have any other associated symptoms, she has not had any injury to the area. Most likely these symptoms are caused from the injection. She can continue trying hot packs and TYLENOL for the symptoms. I do not see any reason for further testing at this time. We did discuss return precautions. If she develops any fevers, chills, chest pain, shortness of breath or any other new or concerning symptoms she is to return for recheck. Patient is comfortable with this plan and is discharged in stable condition. Pt stated via follow up phone call today, 01/05/2018: Pain in arm went away for a couple of days but after sleeping on couch for the night pain came back and cannot lift arm again. Pt states that she is actually unsure if this is connected to vaccine or not, states she may have "torn rotator cuff". Pt states that if symptoms persist she will make an appointment with PCP on Monday.
HISTORY: Hypothyroidism; GERD; Dyslipidemia; Anemia; Diverticulitis; Osteopenia; Arthritis
PRIOR_VAX: Pt states that Tetanus vaccinations have previously made her arms sore.

Total arm swollen and limited use for a week.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt experiencing arm pain. 7 days after vaccination. Pain in shoulder. Unable to raise arm above head.
Rotator cuff issues, hurts to sleep on, get dressed, etc. Patient said she felt pain immediatly upon receiving shot.
Pain in left shoulder where administered, Diagnosed with Encephalopathy. Started having seizures a week later.

Rash began to appear on left inner aspect of arm. It is the only place the rash developed. Had a red dry appearance. Was itchy. Patient came out of the room to inform the nurse. The doctor was notified immediately as well as an extensive reparatory assessment. No wheezing, cough, or vomiting presented while patient remained in the office. 50mg BENADRYL given PO in office and hydrocortisone ointment prescribed script sent to the pharmacy. All activity occurred over about 30 min.

This spontaneous report has been received from an office manager referring to a patient of unknown age and gender. No information was provided regarding the patient's medical history, concurrent conditions, drug, allergy history or concomitant medications. On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose of PROQUAD, (strength, dose and frequency were not provided) lot # N020617, expiration date 22-JAN-2019, for prophylaxis. The doses of PROQUAD were exposed to a temperature excursion of -14°Celsius (°C) to -10°C, during a time frame of 2 hours; -9°C to 8°C (4.48 °C) during a time frame of 4 hours, which was detected by the data logger. There was no previous temperature excursion. No adverse effects were reported.

This spontaneous report was received from a registered nurse referring to a 6 month old female patient. The patient had no relevant medical history, drug reactions/allergies or concomitant medications. The reporter informed that the patient had completed a hepatitis B series with hepatitis b vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis (strength, route, dosage schedule and lot number were not reported) which was administered on 02-JUN-2004, 30-NOV-2004 and 08-MAR-2005. On an unspecified date (reported as "before August 2017"), the patient's had hepatitis B titers drawn and were not where the doctor wanted them to be. The patient did not seek medical attention, but she received treatment for the adverse event. No studies or diagnostic tests were carried out. Then on 18-AUG-2017, the patient was vaccinated with RECOMBIVAX HB lot number: N006321 (expiration date: 08-NOV-2019) and on 20-OCT-2017, the patient received another dose of RECOMBIVAX HB lot number: N002920 (expiration date: 30-SEP-2018). The outcome of hepatitis b surface antibody negative was unknown. The reporter did not assess the relatedness of RECOMBIVAX HB with hepatitis b surface antibody negative.

Patient developed urticaria on trunk and extremities within 1.5 hours of receiving the vaccine. Patient went to ER on 1/3/18 and was diagnosed with allergic reaction, prescribed prednisolone. This spontaneous report was received from a pharmacist and refers to a 54-year-old female patient with unspecified concomitant medications and unspecified pertinent medical history. The patient's concurrent conditions included food-related allergy. On 29-DEC-2017, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of ZOSTAVAX, subcutaneously, lot number N028099 with expiration date 06-JAN-2019 (dose not reported), as vaccine. The ZOSTAVAX was reconstituted with sterile diluent (MERCK), subcutaneously, (dose, frequency, lot number and expiration date were not reported) for prophylaxis. On 30-DEC-2017, the patient returned to the pharmacy with site reaction which was red and warmth to touch. Then, on an unspecified date in December 2017, the patient went to an urgent care and was informed that she had infection due to ZOSTAVAX which was administered too close (about an inch) to a scar; the urgent care prescribed the patient KEFLEX as treatment which was administered. At the time of the report, the patient did not recover from the vaccination site infection. The reporter considered vaccination site infection to be related to ZOSTAVAX.

Information was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a male patient of unknown age. No information was received concerning the patient's past medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medication. On or about 01-JAN-2015, the patient was inoculated with ZOSTAVAX (lot number, dosage, and route of administration not provided), for its intended purpose the prevention of shingles. As a direct result of ZOSTAVAX, on 18-NOV-2015 the patient experienced a shingles outbreak in addition to chronic pain, rash, and lesions to various parts of his body. As a direct result of the vaccine, the patient suffered mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. As a result of ZOSTAVAX the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. As a direct and proximate consequence, the patient has sustained serious personal injuries and related losses, including but not limited to, mental anguish, physical pain and suffering, diminished capacity for the enjoyment of life, a diminished quality of life, medical and related expenses, and other losses and damages. Shingles outbreak and chronic pain were considered disabling. Additional information has been requested.

This is a spontaneous report from a contactable pharmacist, based on the information received by Merck & Co., Inc. (manufacturer control number: 00689118). A patient of unspecified age, ethnicity, and gender received PREVNAR, via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified date at a single dose for immunization. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On an unspecified date, the patient experienced red, irritated area at the injection site that was warm to the touch 5 days after vaccination and it's now growing in size. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of red, irritated area at the injection site that was warm to the touch 5 days after vaccination and it's now growing in size and included treatment with BENADRYL and TYLENOL. The clinical outcome of the event, red, irritated area at the injection site that was warm to the touch 5 days after vaccination and it's now growing in size, was not recovered. No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.

The patient medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. The patient got pneumococcal 13-val conjugate vaccine (dipht crm197 protein) along with the influenza quad vaccine. The patient told the doctor that she had already had the shot but he gave it to her anyway. In addition, after four days she started developing pain in her left leg. This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of autism in a child female patient who received HAVRIX. On an unknown date, the patient received HAVRIX at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving HAVRIX, the patient experienced autism (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the outcome of the autism was unknown. The reporter considered the autism to be almost certainly related to HAVRIX. Additional details were reported as follows: The case was reported by the patient's mother. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient was diagnosed with autism. The reporter firmly believed that the aluminum contained in HAVRIX caused her daughter to be diagnosed with autism. The reporter did not wish to participate in the safety report.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approx 10-14 days after vaccination, patient developed 10 "pox" lesions on face, torso, and legs. He was not seen by a physician for evaluation of rash. Reaction was reported to me at 15 month checkup.
Pt developed rash and warm upper arm later in day after vaccination.

As the nurse put the injection in my arm it hurt more than usual. Then within hours it started hurting more and more. It hurt so bad that I had to take off work for two weeks, I couldn't even raise my arm up I couldn't hold a bottle of water with that hand this went on for over 2 weeks. Even after going back to work I had to alter my routines and make it easy on my shoulder. It's now been months and I still have pain in that shoulder I can't lift heavy things with that arm can't sleep on that arm it still hurts more than right after the average flu shot. Both my family doctor and a nurse at the health department said the shot was put way too high. My family doctor said if the pain continues after I have my baby that she will have x-rays and stuff done to see if she can help the pain at all. This is my fourth pregnancy I am due February 3rd. The pregnancy has been a normal healthy pregnancy.
LAB_DATA: None yet because I am pregnant. If I'm still in pain after I have my baby then my doctor does plan on doing some tests.
OTHER_MEDS: Flintstone vitamins, magnesium supplements on occasion, tramadol
ALLERGIES: Allergic to bloodworms, rats, and MONISTAT

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day after the vaccine was administered, patient starting having high fevers, hives and seizures (or what they thought were true neurological seizures). We rotated TYLENOL and MOTRIN that was recommended by doctor. He had high fevers, hives and seizures for a month. Once the high fevers and hives finally went away, patient still had the seizure episodes and started to have behavioral problems, delays, speech problems and was beyond in his milestones. He was diagnosed with a Sensory Processing Disorder at 2.5 years old and still has what doctors are calling mimicking seizures now caused by migraines but they have not been able to pinpoint exactly what the episodes are or what is causing them.
LAB_DATA: MRIs that have come back normal; unknown date
HISTORY: Sensory Processing Disorder and mimicking seizures that have not been pinpointed on what they truly are
ALLERGIES: Mint, red dyes, eggs, dairy/soy and food dyes

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a male patient of unknown age. Information regarding medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications was not provided. On or about 2016, the patient was inoculated (by an unspecified person) with ZOSTAVAX for routine health maintenance and for the prevention of shingles. The vaccine did not prevent shingles, but rather caused the patient to contract a persistent strain of herpes zoster. After receiving ZOSTAVAX, the patient was diagnosed (by an unspecified person) with postherpectic neuralgia. As a direct and proximate result of these malfunctions, the patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. As a further proximate result, the patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, and pain and suffering, and other damages. As a direct and proximate result of ZOSTAVAX, the patient's symptoms and diagnoses have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the product. As a result of ZOSTAVAX, the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. The events of persistent strain of herpes zoster, postherpectic neuralgia, and vaccination failure were considered to be disabling by the reporter. Additional information has been requested.
Swelling from shoulder to elbow. No hives or fever. Pt states swelling has gone down some but did want to let us know she had a reaction. Pt using ice pack, benadryl, motrin/and tylenol

SYMPTOM_TEXT: ON 01/01/18 (2 WEEKS AFTER IMMUNIZATIONS WERE PROVIDED) AROUND 1900 PARENT NOTICED LEFT ARM HAVING MORE REDNESS AND BLISTERS AROUND INJECTION SITE OF WHERE THE VARICELLA VACCINE WAS GIVEN. DENIES ANY FEVER OR REDNESS PRIOR TO THIS DATE. ON 01/03/18 CHILD WAS TAKEN TO PCP AND PROVIDED A TOPICAL CREAM TO APPLY TO SITE. PCP'S NURSE CALLED ON 1/3/18 TO REPORT THE ADVERSE REACTION. MOM BRINGS CHILD IN TODAY AND NO REDNESS NOTED. SITE STILL HAS CIRCLE OF CRUSTED SPOTS AT INJECTION SITE. MOM VERBALIZES UNDERSTANDING THIS IS NORMAL REACTION AND WILL PLAN TO CONTINUE TO VACCINATE CHILD AS NEEDED.

Received influenza 4 strain Flucelvax flu shot on 10/7/17. Within 7 days, left knee began aching continuously as well as both shoulder joints and rotator cuff popping. Orthopedic doctor took x-rays stating knee required a full replacement and to temporarily relieve the pain administered a cortisone shot to the knee. Pain subsided in knee for 20 days, however the shoulder joints kept getting worse then all my joints in the body became inflamed. Dr ordered multiple blood tests to isolate issue, results indicated an auto immune disease however it is not Rheumatoid Arthritis, not Lupus, not Scleroderma but Sedimentary Rate was very high out of range. Dr prescribed 15mg Meloxicam to ease inflammation however it did not have any affect. Dr prescribed 800mg Dexius (ibuprofen with Pepcid) and this has reduced pain and inflammation 50% but returns to 100% after 8 hours drug wears off. On 12/7/17 Dr has diagnosed, symptom is vaccine induced arthropathy and will take several months to see any improvement.
LAB_DATA: Blood tests during November concluded I do not have Lupus, RA or Scleroderma

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of vaccination failure in a 16-year-old female subject who received Meningococcal ACWY vaccine. Co-suspect products included SOLIRIS for paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria. Concurrent medical conditions included paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria. On an unknown date, 183 days after receiving Meningococcal ACWY vaccine and Meningococcal B Recom vaccine + AIOH + OMV, the subject developed vaccination failure. Serious criteria included death and GSK medically significant. Additional event(s) included meningococcal infection with serious criteria of death and GSK medically significant. The outcome of vaccination failure was fatal. The outcome(s) of the additional event(s) included meningococcal infection (fatal). The reported cause of death was meningococcal infection. The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the vaccination failure and meningococcal infection may have been caused by Meningococcal ACWY and Meningococcal B Recom vaccine + AIOH + OMV. Relevant Tests: Lab tests were performed on an unspecified date. The isolate initially was reported to be serogroup B, but subsequent testing at the Centers  for  Disease  Control  and  Prevention  (CDC) revealed that the strain actually was non-groupable. The isolate sequence type (ST-2578) was associated more commonly with asymptomatic carriage rather than invasive disease. Additional information was provided. This case was reported in a literature article and described suspected vaccination failure in a 16-year-old female patient who was vaccinated with unspecified meningococcal ACWY (MenACWY) vaccine and unspecified meningococcal serogroup B (MenB-4C) vaccine (manufacturers unknown for both). This case corresponds to the meningococcal vaccines section of the article. The patient was a part of the study that provided data from the manufacturer who reported 16 cases of meningococcal disease (including 1 death) in 5207 person-years of eculizumab exposure between 2007 and 2014; the age range was 17 to 45 years, and all of them had received meningococcal vaccination. The patient had paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medications was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received unspecified meningococcal  ACWY  (MenACWY) and unspecified meningococcal  serogroup B (MenB-4C) vaccines (administration route and site unspecified; dosage unknown; batch number not provided for both). The patient had started SOLIRIS. Age of vaccinations was not provided. On an unspecified date, approximately 6 months after vaccinations and 1 month after eculizumab therapy, the patient developed meningococcal disease. The isolate initially was reported to be serogroup B, but subsequent testing at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) revealed that the strain actually was non-groupable. The isolate sequence type (ST-2578) was associated more commonly with asymptomatic carriage rather than invasive disease. On an unspecified date, the patient died despite apparently strong memory antibody response to the strain. Thus, a normally non-pathogenic strain led to fatal illness despite vaccination. It was unknown if an autopsy was performed. This case has been considered as suspected vaccination failure being full schedule was unknown. This case has been considered serious due to death/suspected vaccination failure. Treatment was unknown. The authors stated, "The CDC concluded that vaccination provides incomplete protection to eculizumab recipients". Additionally, the authors mentioned "FDA approved prescribing information includes a black-box warning for increased risk of meningococcal disease in recipients who take eculizumab".
LAB_DATA: Lab tests were performed on an unspecified date. The isolate initially was reported to be serogroup B, but subsequent testing at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) revealed that the strain actually was non-groupable. The isolate sequence type (ST-2578) was associated more commonly with asymptomatic carriage rather than invasive disease.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported by a pharmacist via call center representative and described the occurrence of fever in a adult female patient who received SHINGRIX. On 26th December 2017, the patient received SHINGRIX. In December 2017, 12 hrs after receiving SHINGRIX, the patient experienced fever, myalgia and general body pain. On 27th December 2017, the patient experienced feels awful. In December 2017, the outcome of the feels awful was recovered/resolved. On 28th December 2017, the outcome of the fever, myalgia and general body pain were recovered/resolved. The reporter considered the fever and myalgia to be unrelated to SHINGRIX. It was unknown if the reporter considered the general body pain and feels awful to be related to SHINGRIX. Additional details were provided as follows: The reporting pharmacist was the patient. The age at vaccination was not reported. On 27th December 2017, the patient woke during the night with fever, myalgia and severe body aches. On 27th December 2017, 1 day after vaccination, the patient felt terrible for about 12 hours and then symptoms resolved on their own. The hospital or physician's intervention was not required. The pharmacist called from home on her day off, so lot and expiration date were not available.

No other clarifying information provided. No other information provided.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported by a pharmacist and described the occurrence of pain in arm in a 58-year-old male patient who received FLUARIX Quadrivalent (batch number 5J594, expiry date 5th May 2018. Previously administered products included AFLUIRA with an associated reaction of pain in extremity (received in left and experienced left arm pain). On 31st August 2017, the patient received FLUARIX Quadrivalent (intramuscular) .5 ml. On an unknown date, less than a year after receiving FLUARIX Quadrivalent, the patient experienced pain in arm and injected limb mobility decreased. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain in arm and injected limb mobility decreased were not recovered/not resolved. The reporter considered the pain in arm to be related to FLUARIX Quadrivalent. It was unknown if the reporter considered the injected limb mobility decreased to be related to FLUARIX Quadrivalent. Additional details were reported as follows: The patient received FLUARIX Quadrivalent in right deltoid. The patient noted he had pain from the AFLURIA flu vaccine in 2016, which was given to him in his left arm and that is why he chose the right arm with the present vaccine. The patient had arm pain at the injection area after the vaccine, which he thought it was just the shot, but he continued to have right arm pain still. The patient had a really painful arm which was hurting and he cannot lift his arm beyond the ear. The patient reported these events to the pharmacy in December. The pharmacist was unaware if these events had been reported by the patient to his physician. The patient denied any other vaccines on his questionnaire, when he was asked about other vaccines on this day or 4 weeks prior to this vaccination. It was reported that, the pharmacist who gave the vaccine was no longer working at the pharmacy. The pharmacist stated that, it was their protocol to report to VAERS. She was encouraged to follow her protocols and make aware GlaxoSmithKline would report to VAERS as well. The pharmacist reported that, the patient requested manufacturer's phone number. A search of the patient's name did not find a previous report.
HISTORY: 2016, AFLURIA, Prophylaxis, Pain in extremity, received in left and experienced left arm pain

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Caregiver was given her influenza vaccine by Flu champion on 10/9/17 immediately after vaccine was given, caregiver complained that she didn't feel right. Complained of light headedness, feeling hot and sweaty, tachycardia and nauseous. Caregiver felt better after rest and eating. Was placed in a quiet room to lay down and rest for a bit, O2 was at 98% and pulse between 114-122 which was taken by LPN. After about 20 mins Caregiver did sit up verses laying down as she felt the ceiling was making her more nauseous. After another 10 minutes caregiver did make her way back to her work area to shut down her computer and gather things to bring home as her husband was going to pick her up and she didn't feel comfortable to drive. Caregiver did contact MA about one our later and stated that she ate something and seemed to feel much better.

Within 4 hours of vaccination, the site was swollen, red, and tender to the size of patient's fist around injection site. Within 24 hours, the swelling and redness had expanded to include his whole upper leg from hip bone to just above the knee and all around the thigh. The tenderness caused pain during any movement of the leg and discomfort at rest. 5 mL acetaminophen administered at bedtime to induce sleep. The morning of Jan 6, swelling and redness had not subsided. Itching at the site started.

Congestion and cough with vomiting, rapid breathing that has lasted for 11 weeks (so far). Multiple trips to the doctor and ER in November and December. Have tried albuterol breathing treatments, prednisone, amoxicillin. Have had two chest Xrays and an EEG (after a strange episode of lethargy in December). Went to an ENT on December 26, who is guessing silent reflux may be a culprit (baby doesn't spit up). Currently on a daily dose of ZANTAC 2x a day (4mL). Symptoms persist. If no improvement by follow up appointment at the end of January, ENT will refer us to hospital.
LAB_DATA: December 3, 2017 - xray (inflammation), blood work (normal); December 11, 2017 - EEG (normal); December 31, 2017 - xray (normal)

He cut above his eye so we put pressure and ice on the wound. We elevated his feet and his color came back and he was able to talk and tell us where he was. We called 911 and they took BP, EKG, and pulse; all were within normal. Pt was dizzy when he stood up, and told EMT he "didn't feel right", so they took him to Urgent Care per mom's approval.

As reported by the mother to me the pharmacist. Mother reported her son had coughing and shortness of breath that started within an hour after receiving the flu shot. She gave him some BENADRYL and his symptoms resolved. The next morning her son said that he did not feel well. He vomited, and she told him to go back to bed to rest. Later in the day, he was sleeping and he was unresponsive and not waking up although he was breathing. They took him to the ER. The ER doctor said that his reflexes were not normal. They gave him fluids and ibuprofen and he was better, became responsive. They sent him home and said to watch him and bring him back if any symptoms returned.

Complaints of general back and joint pain within 2 weeks of vaccination. Approximately 4 weeks after vaccination, complaints of severe tiredness, some weakness, and intermittent vomiting (on 24- to 61-hour periodicity). Approximately 5 weeks after vaccination, hospitalized with loss of coordination; inability to walk without assistance (falling); severe jaw, joint, and back pain. CT of head, chest X-ray, blood analyses, lumbar puncture, MRI of brain and spine; diagnosed with Guillain-Barre' Syndrome.  Immediately initiated plasmapheresis (5 treatments), followed by intravenous immunoglobulin treatment (5 treatments beginning after 3rd plasmapheresis treatment). Outcome pending; complete recovery not yet realized. GBS recovery expected to be prolonged; residual paralysis remains; permanent/permanence of damage unknown at this time.
LAB_DATA: November 19, 2017: CT of head, chest X-ray, blood analyses; November 19/20, 2017: Lumbar puncture (analysis of spinal fluid) and MRI of brain and spine. November 21 through December 15, 2017: numerous chest x-rays, ultrasounds, blood tests, etc. MRI revealed inflamed nerves along the spinal column; diagnosed Guillain-Barre' Syndrome. Final results of adverse events not completely understood.
ALLERGIES: None known; adverse reaction to PRECEDEX.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving the vaccine, patient claims her was sore and she could not move it very well without pain. She thought it would go away, but after a little over a week and no improvement, she came to the pharmacy to report it. I told her to go to her PCP and have them examine her. Her PCP could find neither infection nor inflammation and recommended the patient get an MRI to see if there was nerve damage. Have not heard any further from the patient.

Pt left the counseling room and walked around the store for about 5 min. She then said she was feeling heart palpitations, sweaty, and light headed, ran to a chair to sit down and then fainted. The person who was with her woke her up thankfully and we called 911. The patient said her breathing was not affected and that she was allergic to epinephrine, so I did not give her an epipen. The EMS rep directed us not to give any food or drink. When EMS arrived her blood pressure was less than 90/60 and they carried her out in a chair and brought her to the nearest hospital. They did not allow her to stand yet. After regaining consciousness we learned that she got off a plane last night, slept late this morning, only ate a lentil flat bread a few hours prior to getting the vaccine and was already taking Benadryl and Zyrtec.
CUR_ILL: Very mild anemia that is controlled and treated with iron, only ate a small breakfast of lentil flatbread, just got off the plane last night

Next morning start of blisters at shot side, under upper arm and on palm of hand between thumb and 1st first. Small blisters started to appear over full arm. Treated for allergic reaction to shot....shot of BENADRYL, prednisone pills.
LAB_DATA: Evening of shot, red at injection site and substantial swelling on upper arm along with being sore.  Swelling and pain subsided by next day.

OTHER_MEDS: chlorphenermine (new, started same day vaccine administered), doxazosin, valacyclovir, letrozole, Uribel, hydrocodone/APAP, tramadol, Vyvanse

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Per 7 Jan 18 at 1120 medical record entry, patient presents for documentation of flu shot adverse event. States that on 2 Dec 2017 was given the flu vaccine in L deltoid. Around 9 Dec 17 noticed that left arm was sore and become increasingly more sore. Around 17 Dec 17 noticed a break in the skin where the vaccine was given that progressed to becoming wider, edematous, erythematous with scab formation. The area was raw, zero (0) drainage. Had had L shoulder pain since then. The scab resolved within a week. 29 Dec 17 made apt with Dr. who swabbed the scab and was given 1 gram of ROCEPHIN. 30 Dec 17 went to urgent care. Was seen by NP there. The NP believed that the vaccine hit a nerve. Was seen by (Ortho) 2 Jan 18 who believes that the flu shot was given in the nerve. Dr. sent to physical therapy. Reported 5 Jan 18. Went to 1st physical therapy visit was on 5 Jan 18. Physical therapist believes the median nerve was the affected nerve. Can't reach over head or behind her back. Physical therapist did "scraping" of the L deltoid.

Information has been received on 03-JAN-2018 regarding a case in litigation from a lawyer and a female consumer of unknown age and her husband. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history and concomitant medications are unknown. On or about 2014, the patient was inoculated with ZOSTAVAX (lot number and expiration unknown) subcutaneous for routine health maintenance and for the prevention of shingles. The vaccine did not prevent shingles, but rather caused the patient to contract a persistent strain of herpes zoster. Shortly after receiving ZOSTAVAX, the patient developed tremors and memory issues. Thereafter, the patient was diagnosed with encephalitis, which resulted in the patient being in a coma for two weeks. As a direct and proximate result of these malfunctions, the patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. As a further proximate result, the patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, and pain and suffering and other damages. The patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. Upon internal review, encephalitis and coma were considered to be medically significant. Encephalitis, persistent strain of herpes zoster, coma, tremors, and memory issues were considered to be disabling. Additional information has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pain and soreness started in the area of the shot within a few hours. I normally sleep on my left side and have been unable to do so since the injection. The pain increased to a throbbing level over the next three weeks, and is so intense as to restrict left arm motion vertically and rearward. I went to see my PCP at week five, but there was nothing she could offer. The soreness has decreased some, but returns at the end of a day of normal activity such as grocery shopping or light housekeeping. My left arm?s vertical and rearward motion are still limited so it is very difficult if not impossible to back up my car looking over my right shoulder and trying to steer with my left arm. I also am losing strength in my left arm to the point that last week it caused me to fall. I was standing one step up, reached with my right arm, became a little off balance and reached up with my left arm to steady myself on the wall, and could not do so, causing me to then fall to the floor. I am anticipating requiring physical therapy.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient at 3 months was given vaccinations by Dr. Less than 24 hours, patient screamed in his sleep a high pitch sound, which he never screamed prior in his young life. He also had fevers to which I gave him TYLENOL every 4-6 hours for 24 hours as advised by his Pediatrician at the time. When patient awoke in the morning, he made no eye contact and did not respond to me calling his name and stared into space for about 15 minutes. I immediately knew something was wrong and yelled to my mother for help who was visiting. I told her I was taking him to the ER and she persuaded me to stay home and monitor him. He finally just snapped out of what seemed like a trance and suddenly made eye contact and became engaging. I was just so grateful that he was okay and cried tears of joy, but I knew the vaccinations and his seizure episode was related, even though I did not know it was a seizure at the time in 2013. I decided it was in his best interest in order to save his life, and to prevent this from ever happening again, with the possibility of something worse, to terminate him receiving vaccinations. Given vaccines in 2013 at 3 months old. That night had fevers given TYLENOL every 4-6 hours around the clock for 24 hours as advised by his pediatrician Dr. Screamed in his sleep a high pitch sound never heard before. That morning no eye contact. That morning no response to my engagement with him. That morning I rushed to my mother to make her aware and ask for help. Told her I was taking him to the ER. She said to relax, breathe, give him time and he would be okay. He was in a non-responsive/non engaging/no eye contact state for about 15 minutes. When he "snapped" out of it I thought he was okay and had no idea that it was a seizure. I learned when he was in preschool in casual conversation that he had an absence (staring) seizure. My instincts and intuition knew that the vaccinations were related and I never took him back to be to receive additional shots.
None stated.
HISTORY: Autistic disorder of childhood onset; Lack of coordination; Developmental delay disorder; Muscle weakness; History of seizure disorder; Intellectual disability;  Thrombocytosis (HCC)

Four hours after vaccination, I developed arm pain at site of injection and below toward the insertion point of the deltoid and was unable to abduct or extend my shoulder -- I think this was actually an inability to abduct the arm, but the severe pain was certainly a limiting factor. I applied ice, which gave temporary relief of pain, but did not affect pain with attempted motion. I also had pain radiating to the back of my hand, in the "webbing" between my thumb and first finger. About 16 hours after vaccination, I noticed mild redness and tenderness lateral to injection site, but that disappeared after a few hours. I never had redness at the injection site or induration or swelling. I was unable to use my left arm for 3 1/2 days. On day four I had full range of motion of that arm, pain remained, although much diminished. (The pain on days 4-7 was similar to what I've experienced in the first 24 hours after other vaccinations in the past.) From week two through today, I have had full range of motion and no pain EXCEPT for vague nerve pain a couple of times a day that lasts less than a minute, perhaps precipitated by certain movements of that arm.
OTHER_MEDS: EVISTA, calcium citrate with D, ALLEGRA, PREMARIN vaginal cream
HISTORY: mild asthma, multinodular nontoxic goiter, osteoarthritis of spine and left MTP joint

Case  Comment: Although the event influenza and vaccination failure occurred with a plausible temporal relationship, the causality for the event influenza and vaccination failure cannot be assessed with respect to the suspect vaccine as the case lacks the information regarding the strain of influenza with which the patient was diagnosed with influenza, clinical presentation, detailed investigations (swab and blood culture, immunological tests), immune status of the patient prior to vaccination, concurrent medications and relevant medical history. Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a female patient (age unknown). The patient's medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medication use were not provided. On or about 14-AUG-2013 the patient was vaccinated with ZOSTAVAX, (lot# and route unknown) as recommended for routine adult health maintenance and for the prevention of shingles. The vaccine did not prevent shingles as intended, but rather caused the patient to contract a persistent strain of herpes zoster. On or about 11-SEP-2014, the patient was treated by a physician for the onset of a severe vesicular rash accompanied by weakened immune symptoms, which was diagnosed as herpes zoster accompanied by Ramsay Hunt Syndrome (a condition brought on by a shingles outbreak that interferes with facial nerves and causes facial paralysis and hearing loss, secondary to zoster infections.) On or about 30-SEP-2014, the patient sought subsequent treatment from the physician for ongoing symptoms of Herpes Zoster Oticus and Unilateral high frequency sensorineural hearing loss. The patient sought ongoing treatment for these conditions, but will experience hearing loss that is likely permanent and irreversible due to the interferences she has experienced from zoster complications with her ears. The patient has been prescribed VALTREX and prednisone for management of her painful and bothersome symptoms. As a direct and proximate result of these malfunctions, the patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. As a further proximate result, the patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, and pain and suffering, and other damages. Unilateral high frequency sensorineural hearing loss was reported to be disabling. Upon internal review Ramsay-Hunt Syndrome and unilateral high frequency sensorineural hearing loss were considered medically significant events. Additional information has been requested.

Information has been received on 04-JAN-2018 regarding a case in litigation from a lawyer and a male patient of unknown age. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history and concomitant therapy are unknown. The patient was inoculated with ZOSTAVAX (lot number and expiration unknown) subcutaneous on or about 20-AUG-2013, as recommended for routine adult health maintenance and for the prevention of shingles. The vaccine did not prevent shingles as intended, but rather caused the patient to contract a persistent strain of herpes zoster in addition to herpes zoster of the eyelid and Bell's palsy. On or about 14-AUG-2015, the patient was treated at an urgent care clinic for a blistering vesicular outbreak that was diagnosed as severe herpes zoster, or shingles. On or about 18-AUG-2015, the patient was treated at the urgent care clinic for an outbreak that was diagnosed as herpes zoster of the eyelid with lag opthalmos and was ordered to continue antiviral treatments. On or about 25-AUG-2015, the patient received subsequent treatment at the urgent care clinic for ongoing and worsening symptoms, which were diagnosed as "exposure keratitis OS d/t lag opthalmos", 7th nerve palsy related to herpes zoster, and herpes zoster of the eyelid. Bell's palsy is a condition involving permanent contraction of facial muscles, resulting in drooping of the face and lack of muscle function. The patient had consistent treatments at the urgent clinic with an ongoing diagnosis of severe herpes infection, neuralgia of the 7th cranial nerve and herpes zoster of the eyelid. On or about 02-NOV-2015, the patient underwent an operative procedure for repair brow ptosis, canthoplasty and correction eyelid with implant which was performed by a physician at clinic. The patient sought continued treatment at the clinic for his chronic herpes zoster condition. Throughout his extensive treatment, the patient has been prescribed acyclovir in increasing dosages, mineral oil, petrolatum, white (PURALUBE OINTMENT) and latanoprost for management of his painful and bothersome symptoms. As a direct and proximate result of these malfunctions, the patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. As a further proximate result, the patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, pain and suffering and other damages. Bell's palsy/7th nerve palsy/repair brow ptosis/canthoplasty/correction eyelid with implant was considered to be disabling. Upon internal review, Bell's palsy/7th nerve palsy/repair brow ptosis/canthoplasty/correction eyelid with implant and herpes zoster of the eyelid were considered to be medically significant. Additional information has been requested.

Left arm tender after shot given. That night arm was numb. Pain continued and employee reported on 12/8/17 to Employee Health. She was referred to another provider. She did not go and did not respond to email sent on 12/22/17. I spoke with her today. States she hadn't felt the pain "for awhile" until recently going ice fishing. She felt like the cold made her left arm hurt again. She felt the nurse giving the shot gave it too high.

Within 36 hours of the shot I experienced vertigo while lying down and sleeping. The first morning made me dizzy, weak, light headed, with a couple of vertigo spells. I also had a low grade over all headache and an earache in my right ear. I eventually discovered that turning my head to the left while lying down caused the vertigo. in the afternoon, I felt pretty good., but symptoms started again at bedtime and in the morning on Sunday. Monday Jan. 1, was the worst where vertigo was so bad it caused nausea and vomiting almost the entire day. it was a holiday and I couldn't see a doctor until the next day. The next day was not as bad as monday but worse than over the weekend. I was given a shot by my doctor and 2 rx for nausea. That seemed to help. but still continued to get dizzy and vertigo over night and slightly in the morning. Saturday, Jan 6, was the first morning that I woke up feeling nearly normal. I stopped taking nausea meds. This morning, before getting up, I turned my head to the left to see the alarm clock and got vertigo, but not as bad as previously experienced. This makes my morning a little light headed. But I am able to work. So the worst of the symptoms lasted 7 days from the first symptom. But, it does continue to happen. How much longer am I expected to endure this before it disappears completely?  I did also take HepA&B shot with Yellow Fever, however, that was my second shot. I took my first Hep A&B in November with Zero side effects.

On or about July, 13-AUG-2015, the patient was treated by a physician for sudden and worsening pain in his extremities and difficulty moving. The patient was diagnosed with polymyalgia rheumatica, a serious side effect of ZOSTAVAX. Over the course of six additional medical encounters, the patient was treated for his polymyalgia rheumatica, but his healthcare providers were unable to manage his progressive symptoms and pain. Throughout 2016, the patient was treated by the physician on 16 separate medical encounters, in addition to manage his polymyalgia rheumatica, to no avail. The patient was referred to a hematologist for his atypical and uncontrolled presentation of polymyalgia rheumatica. The patient was prescribed a heavy regimen of prednisone, tramadol, allopurinol, and TYLENOL WITH CODEINE for management of his symptoms. As a result of his painful and dystrophic condition, the patient has been significantly limited in his mobility and ability to live independently. The patient is unable to travel because his immune system has become depleted by his disorder. As a direct and proximate result of these malfunctions, the patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. As a further proximate result, the patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, pain and suffering, and other damages. Upon internal review, polymyalgia rheumatica was determined to be medically significant. Polymyalgia rheumatica and debilitating neurological issues were considered to be disabling. Additional information has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: It started with swelling in my cheek that quickly progressed to my lips and face. I went to the ER where it continued to progress to my hands. After the visit to the ER and a shot of epinephrine, DECADRON and VISTARIL, I felt better. I started taking hydroxyzine pamoate and methylprednisolone but by that evening, the condition worsened with welts starting in my hands, arms, then chest, back, head and legs. I went to an urgent care the next day and was given two more drugs to take - ZANTAC (hard to swallow) and Alkron H3 and was told that the reaction would run its course eventually. It started to get better in about 24 hours and then eventually, it went away. It was awful, something I had never experienced.

Information has been received from the authors in a letter to the editor and refers to retrospective epidemiologic assessment involving 3811 employees. The authors found a nonlinear decline in mumps seropositivity over time, with a sharp decrease 13 years after the most recent measles–mumps–rubella (MMR) vaccine dose on the basis of antibody titers obtained at the outset of employee training with the use of the BioPlex 2200 MMRV IgG multiplex flow immunoassay (Bio-Rad). Seropositivity fell below the estimated herd-immunity threshold among those last vaccinated at least 16 years earlier. Since recent mumps outbreaks have occurred in populations that had been vaccinated as children, the findings raise concern about the need for routine administration of MMR vaccine in young adults entering congregated settings, such as colleges and employee training. This case refers to 45 employees of unspecified ages and genders. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history or concomitant medications were not reported. On unspecified dates from 1998 to 2014, 73 patients were vaccinated with two doses of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown) as prophylaxis (dose, frequency, lot number and expiration date were not reported), from which  6 patients developed mumps on unspecified dates. 7 patients received three doses of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown). On unspecified dates from 2015 to 2016,  2 patients were vaccinated with one dose  of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown) as prophylaxis (dose, frequency, lot number and expiration date were not reported). Both patients developed mumps on unspecified dates; 18 patients received two doses of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown) from which 10 developed mumps on unspecified dates; 14 patients received three doses of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown) from which 2 patients developed mumps on unspecified dates. On unspecified date in 2017, 2 patients were vaccinated with one dose of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown) as prophylaxis (dose, frequency, lot number and expiration date were not reported); 3 patients received three doses of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown). And on an unspecified date, 1 patient was vaccinated with one dose of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown). The outcome of the event mumps was not reported.
