This literature marketed report was received from the authors of the published literature article. The authors performed a retrospective chart review to assess hepatitis B titers in children with celiac disease and whether baseline titers were affected by the presence of other autoimmune diseases, gender or vitamin D levels. 67 children that had a baseline hepatitis B titer after the primary vaccine series for hepatitis B were involved. The average age of diagnosis of celiac disease was 6.74 years. The majority (60/67) were diagnosed via endoscopic biopsy while 10.4% (7/67) were diagnosed via serology based on Society of Pediatric Gastroenterology, Hepatology and Nutrition (SPGHAN) guidelines. Thirty-six (53.7%) were male and 31 (46.3%) were female. 60.6% of children (40/66) had normal vitamin D-25 levels. Of the 67 children, 25 (37.3%) had positive hepatitis B surface antibody levels and 42 (62.7%) had negative hepatitis B surface antibody levels. There was no difference in response to the initial primary hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown) series based on gender. Twenty-three percent of children (6/26) with vitamin D levels <30 ng/mL (considered as low) and 45% of children (18/40) with vitamin D levels greater or equal to 30 ng/mL (normal level), had positive hepatitis titers (p=0.07). Twenty-one percent of children (3/14) with an additional autoimmune disease and 42% in children (22/53) without presence of an additional autoimmune disease, demonstrated hepatitis B immunity following primary vaccination (p=0.22). This literature report refers to 22 children of unknown gender (exact age was not provided) with celiac disease. On unknown dates, the patients were vaccinated with hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown) series (dose, route of administration, therapy type, lot# and expiration date were not reported) for prophylaxis. On unknown dates, the patients had negative hepatitis B surface antibody levels. They were not revaccinated due to lack of pediatrician awareness for need of vaccine as child already completed primary vaccine series, parents not making an appointment to get vaccine, and recent awareness of hepatitis B titer status. The outcome of the event was not reported. The authors considered the event to be related to hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown). This is one of two reports received from the same literature article (cross referenced cases: MARRS #1801USA003203). Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1801USA003203.
CUR_ILL: Coeliac disease (confirmed by biopsy or serology)

The average age of diagnosis of celiac disease was 6.74 years. Thirty-six (53.7%) were male and 31 (46.3%) were female. 60.6% of children (40/66) had normal vitamin D-25 levels. Of the 67 children, 25 (37.3%) had positive hepatitis B surface antibody levels (greater than 12 mIU) and 42 (62.7%) had negative hepatitis B surface antibody levels. There was no difference in response to the initial primary hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown) series based on gender. Twenty-three percent of children (6/26) with vitamin D levels <30 ng/mL (considered as low) and 45% of children (18/40) with vitamin D levels greater or equal to 30 ng/mL (normal level), had positive hepatitis titers (p=0.07). Twenty-one percent of children (3/14) with an additional autoimmune disease and 42% in children (22/53) without presence of an additional autoimmune disease, demonstrated hepatitis B immunity following primary vaccination (p=0.22). On unknown dates, the patients were vaccinated with hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown) series (dose, route of administration, therapy type, lot# and expiration date were not reported) for prophylaxis. On unknown dates, the patients had negative hepatitis B surface antibody levels. The patients started a gluten free diet on unknown dates. On unknown dates, the patients were revaccinated with one additional hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown) vaccine. The authors considered the event of negative hepatitis B surface antibody levels to be related to hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown). SYMPTOM_TEXT: Experience severe tachycardia with lethargy, weight loss, intractable nausea and vomiting. Spent a total of 10 day in the hospital. Admitted twice each time was a 5 day stay. Also, had 2 ER visits.  Multiple tests were run. I ultimately ended up with an NG tube to supply nutrition as I was malnourished and lost 12 lbs resulting in me weighing only 102 lbs. I still have the NG tube and am on my 3rd month of sickness. I developed a positive ANA lab test and my IGE was elevated.
LAB_DATA: Cannot remember all the dates as there were multiple test done. Extensive lab work done 11/2017 and 12/2017, Echocardiogram 11/2017, brain MRI 12/2017, HIDA scan 12/2017, abdominal ultrasound 12/2017, CT chest, abdomen and pelvis 11/2017, NG tube placement 12/2017, gastric emptying study 12/2017, chest x ray 11/2017, allergy testing 12/2017, upper endoscopy 11/2017. Elevated IGE level. Positive ANA. Upper endoscopy revealed gastritis and eosinophils on biopsy of stomach.
OTHER_MEDS: CORLANOR; YASMIN; vitamin B-12 injections, vitamin D, gabapentin.
HISTORY: Postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome and inappropriate sinus tachycardia.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt. mom called stating that pt. has an all over "yucky" feeling since getting vaccines. She got shots on 1-8-18, took a nap when she got home. Mom states napping is not unusual. When she awoke, she stated feeling of body aches, hot and cold alternating and headache. Mom said that she took her temperature twice and did not have a fever. She spoke to her doctor's office they said it was from the vaccines and that she should be seen when she has a sore neck. I encouraged mom to have her seen by the doctor to evaluated for other illness as well as possible vaccine reaction. Mom was very thankful for the conversation.

Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a male patient of unknown age. No information was received regarding the patient's past medical history, concurrent condition, or concomitant medication. The patient was inoculated with ZOSTAVAX (lot number, dosage and route of administration not provided) on or about 28-OCT-2014 at a physician's office, as recommended for routine adult health maintenance and for the prevention of shingles. ZOSTAVAX did not prevent shingles as intended, but rather caused the patient to contract a persistent strain of shingles. On or about 07-NOV-2014, the patient was treated at physician's for onset of a severe vesicular rash accompanied by weakened immune symptoms, which was diagnosed as severe herpes zoster, or shingles. The patient has been prescribed diclofenac and gabapentin for management of his painful symptoms. On or about 25-NOV-2014, he had additional treatment for ongoing and worsening symptoms which was then diagnosed as post-herpetic neuralgia, a chronic condition or nerve pain and damage secondary to shingles infections. The patient was prescribed prednisolone along with continuing tramadol for management of his persistent and painful symptoms. As a direct and proximate result of these malfunctions, the patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. As a further proximate result, the patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, and pain and suffering, and other damages. Additional information has been requested.

This case was reported by a physician via call center representative and described the occurrence of blurred vision in a 12-year-old female patient who received BOOSTRIX. On 14th August 2017, the patient received BOOSTRIX .5 ml. On 15th September 2017, 32 days after receiving BOOSTRIX, the patient experienced blurred vision (serious criteria disability), myopia (serious criteria disability), creatine phosphokinase increased (serious criteria disability) and feeling unwell. On 16th September 2017, the patient experienced walking difficulty (serious criteria disability), increased reflexes (serious criteria disability), myalgia of lower extremities (serious criteria disability), lower extremities weakness of (serious criteria disability), dizziness (serious criteria disability) and unable to walk. On an unknown date, the patient experienced paresthesia (serious criteria disability) and numbness (serious criteria disability). The patient was treated with Ear Drops {NOS} and TYLENOL. On an unknown date, the outcome of the blurred vision, walking difficulty, increased reflexes, paresthesia, numbness, myalgia of lower extremities, lower extremities weakness of, dizziness and unable to walk were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the myopia was unchanged and the outcome of the creatine phosphokinase increased and feeling unwell were unknown. The reporter considered the blurred vision, walking difficulty, increased reflexes, myopia, creatine phosphokinase increased, paresthesia, numbness, myalgia of lower extremities, lower extremities weakness of and dizziness to be possibly related to BOOSTRIX. It was unknown if the reporter considered the unable to walk and feeling unwell to be related to BOOSTRIX. Additional details were reported as follows: The physician was a pediatrician who did not work at the location where the vaccine was administered to the patient, who said that the nurse practitioner was responsible for the vaccine's administration at the clinic where the vaccine was administered. The patient's concomitant medication included ear drops starting from 14th August 2017. The reporter described that the patient's vision changed as being blurred vision but that was a subjective symptom because the pediatric eye examination was normal. On 15th September 2017, 32 days after vaccination, the patient was not feeling well, blood creatine phosphokinase increased and had myopia. The leg muscle pain was described as occurring in both legs with leg weakness in both legs. The difficulty in ambulating was described as the patient being unable to walk for more than a few steps. The dizziness occurred in the evening on the same day as the leg muscle pain with weakness and ambulation difficulty, which had occurred in the morning. On 16th September 2017, 33 days after vaccination, the patient experienced ambulation difficulty, mildly brisk reflexes, leg muscle pain and weakness, dizziness and unable to walk. On 16th September 2017 and 12th October 2017, the patient went to the emergency room because of the symptoms but was not admitted. The medical workup for this patient now included an ophthalmologist visit in which she was diagnosed with myopia and nothing else. The recent Blood creatine phosphokinase test results were pending. The patient recently started having numbness, tingling, and paresthesias which had been waxing and waning day to day. Less than a year after vaccination the patient experienced paresthesias, tingling, and numbness. On 13th October 2017, the patient was seen by a neurologist and the exam results were inconclusive, excepting diagnosis of mildly brisk reflex. On 13th October 2017, the patient had a normal cardiology workup. The patient had a pending Electroencephalography. The patient's parents were distraught and the reporter said these symptoms had been disabling that she had not been able to go back to school and was still unable to walk on her own most of the time. All of the symptoms were still waxing and waning from day to day. The reporter said the myopia could just be a baseline physical finding and was unsure if it was related to all of the other symptoms. The reporter gave permission to be contacted by GCSP. The reporter had no specific dosing details for the vaccine beyond what was documented already above.
LAB_DATA: 09/15/2017, Blood creatine phosphokinase, 96; 09/16/2017, Blood creatine phosphokinase, 105; 2017, Electroencephalogram, pending; 10/13/2017, Neurological examination, inconclusive, excepting diagnosis of mildly brisk; 11/17/2017, Nuclear magnetic resonance imaging brain, normal; 11/17/2017, Nuclear magnetic resonance imaging spinal, normal; 09/2017, Ophthalmological examination, normal; 10/13/2017, Physical examination, normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This serious initial spontaneous case, was received from other non-healthcare professional on 25-Sep-2017, concerning a male patient of unspecified age. On 13-Sep-2017, the patient was administered with FLUAD (dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration, anatomical location, batch number, expiry date: not reported). It was reported that, the patient experienced chills followed by fever, in several episodes. On 22-Sep-2017, the most severe episode occurred with fever raised to 103.9 F. The patient also experienced aches and pains and he felt as if he was having the flu. On 25-Sep-2017, at 1:00 pm, chills began and stopped at 03:00 pm. It was reported that the patient wrapped himself in blanket and fever began with flu symptoms. The patient was treated with TYLENOL. Chills were stopped. The outcome of the event flu symptoms was not recovered.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Employee received vaccine at 9:10 am and left the facility to return to work shortly after. Employee drove approximately 16 blocks and felt like her blood pressure was dropping. Employee was having a difficult time breathing. Employee parked her car into a parking lot. Employee had liquid BENADRYL with her and took 5 mls. Employee called 911 for assistance. The 911 connected employee to the local fire department. The fire department provided information regarding the closest hospital locations. Employee then called her supervisor who directed employee to return to the employee immunization clinic. Employee returned to the clinic at 9:45 am. Employee was assessed by this nurse. Vital signs at 10:00 am: Blood pressure: 118/78, pulse: 64, respirations: 16. Breathing was normal, skin: cool, clammy and intact. Employee was able to talk and swallow normally. Patient alert and oriented to person, place and time. Vital signs repeated at 10:20 am: B/P: 108/68, pulse 60, respirations: 16, skin: warm, dry and intact. Employee oriented to person, place and time. V/S at 11:00 am: B/P: 104/62. pulse: 64, respirations: 16, skin warm, dry and intact. Employee oriented to person, place and time.
PRIOR_VAX: Flu vaccine: vasovagal response x 2 years ago ( 2016)
ALLERGIES: CIPRO, LEVAQUIN, Profolol, Food: multiple food allergies; None to latex

This initial spontaneous case was received on 29-Sep-2017, reported by a pharmacist and concerning 42-year-old, adult, female patient. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On 29-Sep-2017, pharmacist while administering FLUAD (dose: 0.5 ml, batch number: 178601, expiry: Apr-2018, PTC number: 1024959, route of administration and indication was not reported) to a patient the syringe tip cracked and it squirted into her eye (explicitly coded as occupational exposure while administering product) caused headache and blurred vision. The pharmacist wanted to know what to do. As a treatment, the pharmacist flushed her eyes with refreshed eye drops. It was reported that, no vaccine was administered or squirted onto the patient. As per the PTC (product technical complaint) investigation performed, package condition, syringe were not damaged and no crack in hub, no signs of leakage was observed and it was concluded that, FLUAD batch 178601 was manufactured in compliance with the approved internal procedures and in accordance with the quality requirements. The sample was not available for analysis. No trends were identified, and that remained the only complaint for FLUAD batch 178601. As a result, no internal root cause had been determined as the most likely root cause and the complaint was considered as not determinable. Since internal root cause was ruled out. Outcome of the events were not reported. This reporter considered the events as non-serious. Non-significant follow-up report received on 29-Sep-2017: PTC reference number (1024959) was updated. Amended narrative accordingly. Follow up received on 20-Nov-2017: The PTC investigation results were update. The narrative was amended accordingly.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Initial unsolicited report received from the literature on 04-Jan-2018. The following is verbatim from the article: The Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP), a group of medical and public health experts, meets 3 times per year to develop recommendations for vaccine use. The group has 15 voting members, and each member's term is 4 years. ACIP members and Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) staff discuss the epidemiology of vaccine-preventable diseases and vaccine research, effectiveness, safety data, and clinical trial results. Representatives from multiple agencies are present as liaisons to the ACIP. The ACIP met on June 21 to 22, 2017, to discuss catch-up vaccination for hepatitis A vaccine, influenza surveillance, influenza vaccine effectiveness, herpes zoster vaccine, the effect of varicella vaccination on the incidence of herpes zoster, meningococcal disease in patients taking eculizumab, and considerations for a potential third dose of MMR vaccine to combat ongoing mumps outbreaks. Updates on dengue virus epidemiology, Zika virus vaccines, anthrax vaccine, yellow fever vaccine, and the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System were given also. This case involves a 16-year-old female patient who was vaccinated with doses of MENACWY VACCINE and MENB-4C VACCINES (batch number, expiry date, dose, dose in series, route and site of administration were not reported for both the vaccines) on an unspecified date. The patient had medical history of paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria. Concomitant medication includes eculizumab for paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria which started on an unknown date approximately one month earlier. On an unspecified date, six months following the vaccinations, the patient experienced fatal meningococcal disease and vaccination failure. Laboratory investigation and corrective treatment were not reported. On an unknown date, the patient died despite apparently strong memory antibody response to the strain. It was unknown if autopsy was performed or not. List of the documents held by sender: none. Sender's Comments: Vaccination failure may be expected with any vaccine, as no vaccine protects all vaccinated individuals. Concomitant medication in this report of fatal meningococcal disease included eculizumab for paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria. Eculizumab is a terminal complement inhibitor and therefore increases patient risk for meningococcal infections. Patients treated with eculizumab and without a history of prior vaccination are recommended to receive a meningococcal vaccine at least 2 weeks prior to receiving the first dose of eculizumab and be revaccinated according to current medical guidelines for vaccine use. In this case, vaccination with MenACWY and MenB meningococcal vaccines occurred prior to initiating treatment with eculizumab. Importantly, this case does not represent a confirmed vaccine failure to MenACWY because information on the specific serogroup involved was not available. The isolate initially was reported to be serogroup B, but subsequent testing revealed that the strain actually was nongroupable. Reported Cause(s) of Death: Fatal meningococcal disease.

Adverse reactions/events and outcomes: Patient received FLUVIRIN on 04-Oct-2016 at pharmacy and was diagnosed with influenza on 08 March 2017. On 08Mar2017 Influenza was diagnosed. Patient was treated with TAMIFLU. On 24-Mar-2017 the events was reported as recovered and the event vaccination failure was updated to unknown. Reporter's Assessment: The other non Healthcare Professional assessed the causality as related. This report was serious (medically significant). Follow-up report received on 24-Apr-2017: It was confirmed that patient had no any medical history. Patient was healthy at the time of vaccination (immunological status). It was reported that patient has been previously immunised and first flu vaccine was of two doses. Nasopharyngeal swab,  blood culture and serology were performed, but diagnosis of influenza was confirmed with nasal swab. Follow up received on 09-May-2017: Batch review report (reference number [1021187] received from quality assurance department on [09-May-2017]: Based on the document review, it was stated that the concerned [FLUVIRIN]  was manufactured in accordance with approved internal procedures and it was in compliance with the current good manufacturing practices (cGMP) requirements.
LAB_DATA: Nasopharyngeal swab, blood culture and serology; Diagnosis of influenza confirmed with nasal swab

This spontaneous case, initially received on 30-Mar-2017 was reported by an other non-health professional (consumer) and concerns about 11 Years old male patient. Administration of Company suspect drug: FLUVIRIN was administered for Influenza immunization on 04-Oct-2016 (Dose: 0.5ml, via intramuscular route of administration, solution dosage form where frequency was one single dose and batch number was not reported). Patient was previously immunized with a first dose of flu vaccine. Adverse reactions/events and outcomes: On 04-Oct-2016, the patient received FLUVIRIN at pharmacy. On 11-Mar-2017 the patient also experienced fever and cough. He was diagnosed with influenza on an unspecified date in Mar 2017. At the time of vaccination the patient was healthy and had no medical history. Nasal swab confirmed influenza. The patient was treated with TAMIFLU. On 13-Mar-2017, the events were reported as recovered / resolved. Reporter's Assessment: The reporter assessed the causality as related. Follow up received on 24-Apr-2017: Patient's immunological status, prior vaccination details, information regarding medical history and lab test were updated. Follow up received on 09-May-2017: Since the batch number was not reported, a batch specific review could not be performed. Based on the Annual Product Review (APR) of FLUVIRIN vaccine, it was concluded that FLUVIRIN manufacturing process was operated at a good level of overall control and the supporting systems are effective in supporting the compliant production, testing and supply processes for FLUVIRIN vaccine. From this conclusion there was no reason or explanation to account for the reported adverse event.

This initial spontaneous case, received on 02-Nov-2017, reported by other non-health professional and concerns a 12-year-old female patient of weight: 48.3 kg, height: 148 cm. The patient's historical condition included stomach pain throughout the years. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. On an unspecified date, the patient received Influenza vaccine (dose, route, anatomical location, trade name and manufacturer was not reported). On 20-Oct-2017, the patient was also received ILARIS (300 mg, subcutaneous, once a (as reported)) for TRAPS (tumor necrosis factor receptor associated periodic syndrome). On an unspecified date, after receiving INN flu vaccine seasonal (reported as two and half weeks ago) and ILARIS injection on 20-Oct-2017, the patient had bad injection site reactions. She used topical BENADRYL but it had no effect, hence it was replaced with oral BENADRYL which helped, but one of the reaction sites returned about in 10 days. On 29-Oct-2017, as soon as BENADRYL was stopped, since then she had bad stomach pain, was tired, appetite lost and was not going to school. It was also reported that, the site reaction that returned was  noticeable, burned and itched, but not as large as it originally was. The patient was not eating and sleeping all the time. She had an intense feet pain (pain level: 5.5). It was reported that, the patient had reoccurring stomach pain throughout the years, she was on ILARIS but not to the intensity that it  did not go away like it was then. She also felt like she was being punched in the stomach. The reporter also reported that, ILARIS reduced length of flare and blood work looked good a month ago, for the first time and had normal sedimentation rate. The outcome of the event injection site reaction was recovering and for events stomach pain, loss of appetite, tiredness and intense foot pain was not recovered (ongoing). The outcome of the other events was not reported.
LAB_DATA: Blood work and sedimentation rate found normal.

Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a male patient of unknown age. No information was received regarding the patient's past medical history, concurrent condition, or concomitant medication. On or about 01-JUL-2011, the patient was vaccinated with ZOSTAVAX (lot number, dosage and route of administration not provided) at physician's office, as recommended for routine adult health maintenance and for the prevention of shingles. The ZOSTAVAX did not prevent shingles as intended, but rather caused the patient to contract a persistent strain of herpes zoster. On or about 27-OCT-2017(conflicting dates), the patient was treated by a physician for the onset of a severe vesicular rash accompanied by weakened immune symptoms, which was diagnosed as herpes zoster, or shingles. On or about 06-NOV-2014 (conflicting dates), the patient received subsequent medical treatment from the physician for ongoing and worsening symptoms of shingles. On or about 14-NOV-2014,(conflicting dates), he was again treated by the physician for uncontrolled symptoms of zoster, at which time his medications were changed in attempts to curb his symptoms. The patient has been prescribed valacyclovir (VALTREX), acetaminophen and hydrocodone (NORCO), and gabapentin(NEURONTIN) for management of his painful symptoms.  As a direct and proximate result of these malfunctions, the patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. As a further proximate result, the patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, and pain and suffering, and other damages. Additional information has been requested.

This non-serious initial spontaneous case, was received from a Pharmacist on 23-Oct-2017, concerning an elderly female patient of 68 years. On 30-Aug-2017, the patient was administered with FLUAD (TIV) (dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: left Deltoid, batch number: 178301, expiry date: Apr-2018). On an unspecified date (between 02-Sep-2017 to 03-Sep-2017), the patient developed "indention" (like a hole) on her arm where injection was given. She had a dimple greater than a quarter dollar coin in the site of the indentation. She went to her physician and he said he had never seen a reaction to a flu vaccine like that and no treatment was recommended for the same. Patient also mentioned that the physician had confirmed the described reaction was from the flu shot. On an unknown date, the patient also experienced headache since she got the vaccine and never had headaches before. It was reported that the patient still had a scar. The indentation had not gone, and the patient kept visiting to the pharmacy to seek advice. The reporter stated that the patient did not receive any treatment measures for the events. At the time of this report, the patient had not yet recovered from the event. The reporter assessed the event as non-serious. Follow up received from the reporter on 14-Nov-2017: Updated age of the patient, added event headache and reporter's comment. Accordingly, updated narrative.

This initial spontaneous case, was received from other non-health professional on 23-Oct-2017, concerns a 65-year-old elderly male patient, weighing 140 lbs and height of 66 inches. The patient underwent lensetomy on an unspecified date. Historical condition included dysinteria (dates not reported). Current condition included low blood pressure since an unspecified date. The patient was broad-shouldered, with a 30-inch waistline. The patient was fit, muscular and athletic. The patient's resting heart rate was 53 and did not have any known allergies. On 18-Aug-2017, the patient was administered with FLUAD (TIV) (dose: 0.5 ml, anatomical location: left arm, batch no: 178601, expiry date: Apr-2018 and route of administration: not reported). It was reported that, approximately 1 week after the vaccination, the patient suffered from a systemic attack and the patient was unsure of what system. On 26-Aug-2017 or on 27-Aug-2017, the patient went for swimming. After a few strokes, he had to stop as he felt soreness in his both elbows. Since that time, he had done little swimming and no push-ups at all. The patient also experienced tenderness. On an unspecified date, the patient went to gym to lift weights and he was unable to lift it from the rack. Bilateral arms triceps would twitch after lifting bars at the gym. He also tried doing push-up but he couldn't do more than 3, prior he could do many triceps before the flu shot. The patient also had soreness in his left arm. He recalled thinking that he was coming down with an illness of some kind. He experienced extreme weakness in bilateral arms and he could not exercise as he was not getting enough strength. In the following week he began to experience a number of physical maladies. From time to time his biceps would twitch in tandem and then they would be sore for few minutes or for few hours. As per patient, soreness caused mild discomfort but no pain, but an annoyance. The same thing would happen to his triceps, in tandem and subsequently the same phenomenon would appear in his forearms. From time to time, he found himself walking slowly, with mild discomfort in both groins. At the time of this report, he was able to function but not well and bilateral events had occurred several times over the course of the last 6-8 weeks (patient estimates it in dozens, occurring constantly, but at levels too slow to be perceived). In addition to these, the patient's hands were quick to fall asleep holding his cell phone, a book, or other small object. The patient stated that his arm fell asleep, but not in the usual way. He did not experience any constriction of blood flow but weakness and tingling. It used to happen any time and frequently happened at night (not every night but often). As the day passed by frequently felt tightening in his chest on the left side. In the past two or three weeks, he developed a strange sleeping pattern. Shortly after returning home from work, and eating, he "shut down" and fall asleep at 7:30 or 8 o'clock and used to awake 4 or 5 hours later, rested, but in a light sweat, with a mild headache or nausea, or all three. Again, he used to fall asleep at 4:30 or 5 AM, sleep restfully for 2 hours and awaken remarkably refreshed. His appetite has remained good throughout this ordeal, however in the absence of exercise he ate less and, consequently, his weight remained the same. About a month ago, the patient completely stopped taking alcohol otherwise he used to take moderate intake of alcohol. In the course of these past two months, a few things had been constant. Patient had experienced soreness at the site of the flu injection, and the weakness in his left arm had been more pronounced than his right. His elbows were both tender, not to the touch, but all on their own. On 30-Sep-2017, the patient found himself resting his left arm on the armrest, and then holding it in his right hand and he described it as it was like "fighting through the distress". On an unspecified date (reported as this Sunday), his left forearm began to ache and he struggled to maintain his composure. A day later the achiness had abated substantially. The patient was also diagnosed by carpal tunnel syndrome, but an EMG at Neurology has ruled it out, finding no nerve and muscle damage in his arms, wrists, and hands. On an unspecified date, the patient underwent EKG (electrocardiogram), a cat-scan (computed tomography), a lung x-ray and blood work which were all found negative (as reported). The patient did not have lyme disease or apparent autoimmune disease, but had been diagnosed with weakness caused by stress. He also experienced life-altering frustration, confusion, and fear. He had struggled to maintain the quality of his work, given up driving as he was fearful that his arms will fail him. The patient stated his social life had dwindled, healthy sex life had ground to a halt and pursuit of his hobbies had suffered. The patient was not given just a flu-shot, he was administered with an adjuvant intended to boost his immune system and he believed, the adjuvant was the cause of his distress. It was reported that, several weeks ago, one of his old friend and colleague reached out to shake his hand and when he extended it, they grasped his hand. He crumpled into his arms in pain. Since then, the patient reflexively recoil from an outstretched hand. On 20-Oct-2007, the patient began sauna sessions 2-3 twenty-minute sauna sessions daily, one in the morning before work, one or two in the evening depending on whether the patient swam at the gym. The first night after sauna, patient did not have night sweats or a sense of elevated fever. Before sauna visits, patient woke up every night with just under 100-101F fever and mild night sweats. Patient also noticed he no longer experienced mild nausea once starting sauna visits. Patient states he had no moisture on face or body after sauna initially, and felt the squalene adjuvant may have been preventing his body from sweating. After 1 week of sauna visits, sweat began to roll off face, and after 2 weeks of sauna visits, body is sweating normally. It was reported that, over past 2 days myalgia and heavy arms are improving and slept for 6 hours for the first time since the symptoms began. On an unspecified date, the patient recovered from the event "left forearm began to ache", myalgia and heavy arms. Outcome of other events were not reported. The reporter did not provided the seriousness assessment and considered the events as related to the influenza vaccine. The patient stated that he suspected the flu-shot as the origin of his ills. The patient was not given just a flu-shot, he was administered with an adjuvant intended to boost his immune system and he believed the adjuvant is the cause of his distress. The patient suggested the marketing of FLUAD be more informative that an adjuvant is contained in the vaccine and he believed consumers might misled. Patient believed he either had a bad reaction to FLUAD, got a bad batch, or was administered an overdose of vaccine. It was reported that as he was 65 years he would receive a double dose. Follow-up received on 08-Nov-2017: Added new events, 100-101 F fever, mild sweats, heavy arms, adverse event NOS, overdose. The outcome of the events myalgia and heavy arms were updated as recovering. Narrative amended accordingly.
LAB_DATA: On an unspecified date, the patient underwent CTA scan of head and neck which revealed nothing wrong. On an unspecified date, the patient underwent EKG, a cat scan, a lung x-ray and blood work, results: negative
HISTORY: Eye operation, at 17 years old; Dysentery

It was reported that FLUAD (Influenza Vaccine, Adjuvanted) is to be stored protected from light and refrigerated between 36 degrees F and 46 F (2 degrees C and 8 degrees C) as stated in the approved product label and must not be freeze. SYMPTOM_TEXT: This initial spontaneous case, was received on 13-Oct-2017, from a pharmacist, concerning a 70-year-old female patient. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On 27-Sep-2017, the patient received FLUAD (TIV) (dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular: anatomical location: left deltoid, batch number: 178623 (as reported) and expiry date: Apr-2018). On 28-Sep-2017, the patient had dark redness (3 inches in diameter) and warmth around injection site. It was reported that, the patient did not receive any medications as a treatment. On an unspecified date (reported as within 2-5 days), the patient had recovered from the events. The reporter considered this case as non-serious. Follow-up received on 23-Oct-2017: The event outcome was changed from not reported to recovered (within 2-5 days). Narrative amended accordingly.

This initial spontaneous case, was received from pharmacist on 20-Oct-2017, concerning a 23-year-old adult female patient. The patient had no relevant medical history and she did not receive any concomitant medications. On 20-Oct-2017, the patient was administered with FLUAD (dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: left deltoid, batch number: 179103, expiry date: May-2018). The patient under 65 years of age received the vaccine (explicitly coded as inappropriate age at vaccine administration). The reporter assessed the event as non-serious.

On the night of the injection an intense headache began that included the back of the head and the neck, the injection site became very sore to the touch, a sleepless night due to a general malaise. In the morning there was intense pain in all the joints which continued, with the headache and a flash feverish feeling. After 24 hours the symptoms were less but prohibitive. Chest congestion started. It's now been 48 hours and the headache and join pain is mostly gone but the injection site has a rash that has spread a few inches down. and there is considerable chest congestion.
Fever spiking at 103.2 that has lasted three days and now we're on to day 4. Baby is not eating as well as normal, and he seems to be feeling very sick: clingy, tired eyes, crying randomly.

This spontaneous report was received from a medical assistant and refers to a patient of unknown age and gender. The patient's concurrent conditions and medical history were not reported. On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose of PROQUAD lot # N021727, expiration date 06-FEB-2019, (dose, route and frequency were not reported) for prophylaxis; administered along with a properly stored sterile diluent, Lot # N016995, expiration date 08-OCT-2019 (dose, route and frequency were not reported). The improperly stored vaccine was noticed due to a data logger. It was stored between 15 Fahrenheit degrees (F) and 46 F (average of 37 F) during 24 hours; and there was a second excursion between 6 F and 14 F (average of 11 F) during 1 hour. There were no previous temperature excursions. No adverse effects were reported. No product quality complaint (PQC) was involved.

Information has been received from the authors of the published literature article. The authors used Social Media's Public Streams Application Programming Interface (API) to collect live data. Between November of 2014 and January 2015, they systematically endeavored to select an optimal set of terms that would be parsimonious enough to be feasible yet broad enough to capture sufficient relevant information. Of the 2,000 comments, 1,887 (94.4%) were relevant to human papillomavirus (HPV). Thus, these 1,887 comments composed their final data-set. The vast majority of comments (n=1,668, 88.4%) originated from unique user accounts. Two hundred and four comments (10.8%) were from users who posted between two and five times, and 30 (1.6%) were from users who posted 10 or more times. Ninety-five (5.0%) comments were coded as having negative sentiment. These comments generally discouraged GARDASIL or GARDASIL 9 vaccination or expressed a particularly negative view toward it. Specific terms characteristic of these comments included "beware," "destroys lives," and "mystery illness." While sentiments were nearly always directly incorporated in to the comments themselves, negative sentiment could also often be inferred by the hashtags at the end of the comment. 78 (4.1%) comments explicitly claimed lack of safety. Examples of phrases included in comments describing lack of safety included "GARDASIL or GARDASIL 9 ruins live [sic]" and "girl dies shortly after receiving HPV vaccine." This case concerns to a healthy 12-year-old girl who died shortly after receiving HPV vaccine. The case was coded as lack of safety 77 (4.1%). The reporter considered death to be related to GARDASIL 9 and/or GARDASIL. Upon internal review death was considered to be a medically significant event. This is one of 2 reports derived from the same literature source, linked to case # 1801USA003508. Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1801USA003508.

Information has been received from the authors of the published literature article. The authors used a Public Streams Application Programming Interface (API) to collect live data. Between November of 2014 and January 2015, they systematically endeavored to select an optimal set of terms that would be parsimonious enough to be feasible yet broad enough to capture sufficient relevant information. Of the 2,000 responses, 1,887 (94.4%) were relevant to human papillomavirus (HPV). Thus, these 1,887 composed their final data-set. The vast majority (n=1,668, 88.4%) originated from unique user accounts. Two hundred and four tweets (10.8%) were from users who posted between two and five times, and 30 (1.6%) were from users who posted 10 or more times. Ninety-five (5.0%) were coded as having negative sentiment. These  generally discouraged GARDASIL or GARDASIL 9 vaccination or expressed a particularly negative view toward it. Specific terms characteristic of these tweets included "beware," "destroys lives," and "mystery illness." While sentiments were nearly always directly incorporated in to the responses themselves, negative sentiment could also often be inferred by the hashtags at the end. 78 (4.1%) explicitly claimed lack of safety. Examples of phrases included in tweets describing lack of safety included "GARDASIL or GARDASIL 9 ruins live [sic]" and "girl dies shortly after receiving HPV vaccine." This case concerns to a girl who died shortly after receiving HPV vaccine. The case was coded as lack of safety 77 (4.1%). The reporter considered death to be related to GARDASIL 9 and/or GARDASIL. Upon internal review death was considered to be a medically significant event. This is one of 2 reports derived from the same literature source, linked to case # 1801USA001975. Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1801USA001975:

The patient was treated with dexamethasone, ibuprofen, famotidine, diphenhydramine, azithromycin, acyclovir, clindamycin, piperacillin sodium, Piperacillin + Tazobactam, oseltamivir and Immunoglobulin. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, influenza B virus infection, fever, nasal congestion, rhinorrhea, myalgia, eruption facial, pruritus facial, skin lesion, tachycardia, tachypnea, papule, skin plaque, vesicles, erythropapular rash, lymphadenopathy cervical, lip dry, leukocytosis, keratinocyte necrosis, interface dermatitis, skin fragility, skin erosion and generalized eruption were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the Stevens Johnson syndrome was resolved with sequelae and the outcome of the scleral hyperemia and post inflammatory hypopigmentation were unknown. The reporter considered the vaccination failure, influenza B virus infection, Stevens Johnson syndrome, fever, nasal congestion, rhinorrhea, myalgia, eruption facial, pruritus facial, skin lesion, tachycardia, tachypnea, papule, skin plague, vesicles, erythropapular rash, lymphadenopathy cervical, scleral hyperemia, lip dry, leukocytosis, keratinocyte necrosis, interface dermatitis, skin fragility, skin erosion, generalized eruption and post inflammatory hypopigmentation to be related to Influenza vaccine unspecified. Additional information was provided. This case was reported in a literature article and described the vaccination failure in a 2-year-old male who was vaccinated with unspecified seasonal trivalent inactivated influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown). The patient was a previously healthy boy. The patient's household contact had experienced "flu" symptoms before current symptom onset. No information on concomitant medication or concurrent condition was provided. On an unspecified date, at the age of 9, 12 and 23 months, the patient received 3 doses of unspecified seasonal trivalent inactivated influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified; batch number not provided) without incident. The patient's immunizations were up to date. On an unspecified date in the Winter of 2013, 3 months after vaccination, the patient presented with a 5-days history of fever, congestion, rhinorrhoea, myalgia, and a progressive pruritic facial eruption. 2 days before, his paediatrician had started dexamethasone, ibuprofen, famotidine, and diphenhydramine because of suspicion of an allergic skin eruption. There were no known medication exposures, including acetaminophen or ibuprofen, preceding the appearance of skin lesions. Over the next 2 days, skin lesions became widespread, prompting re-evaluation. Vital signs were significant for fever 101 degree F, tachycardia, and tachypnea with normal blood pressure. Skin examination revealed pink, annular, oedematous papules and plaques on the face, trunk, buttocks, and extremities, many with dusky, violaceous centres. Multiple tense vesicles and targetoid erythematous papules were located perianally. Rare serous vesicles were noted centrally, with negative Nikolsky and Asboe-Hansen signs. There was no skin tenderness. Additional findings included cervical lymphadenopathy, mildly injected sclera, and dry crusted lips. There was no genital or palmoplantar involvement. The remainder of the physical examination was unremarkable. Laboratory evaluation revealed leukocytosis (17 x 10E9/L) and high C-reactive protein (10 mg/L). Empiric therapy with azithromycin, acyclovir, and clindamycin was initiated while serologic titers and cultures (urine, skin, blood) were pending. Because of continued fever, piperacillin/tazobactam was added on hospital day 2. A nasopharyngeal swab was positive for influenza B and negative for mycoplasma and 18 other common respiratory pathogens according to a respiratory viral polymerase chain reaction (PCR) panel. Oseltamivir therapy was initiated and supportive care provided. Skin biopsy revealed necrotic keratinocytes within the epidermis and an interface dermatitis consistent with the erythema multiforme/Stevens-Johnson syndrome (EM/SJS) spectrum of inflammatory dermatoses. Immunofluorescence studies were negative for immunobullous disease. Antistreptolysin O (ASO), mycoplasma, parvovirus, herpes simplex virus (HSV), Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), and cytomegalovirus titres; surface bacterial and viral cultures; blood culture; and urine culture were negative, and acyclovir and antibiotics were subsequently discontinued. Despite supportive therapy, the patient's eruption rapidly progressed to involve more than 10% of his body surface area, with skin fragility and denudation, requiring transfer to intensive care. Wound care and fluid management continued, and given the progression of cutaneous disease, intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIg) 1 g/kg/d was administered for 3 days, resulting in defervescence and skin stabilization. The patient's lesions re-epithelialized and he was discharged on hospital day 7. He was well with minimal post inflammatory hypopigmentation noted 3 months after hospital discharge. During the following influenza season, after discussion with vaccine safety experts, the child received an unspecified inactivated quadrivalent influenza vaccine containing both influenza B lineages with close monitoring. He tolerated the vaccine well, without any reported adverse reaction after vaccination. The patient subsequently received two additional annual intranasal live attenuated trivalent influenza vaccines without incident. This case has been considered serious due to hospitalisation/vaccination failure. The authors commented, 'After considering available information, experts concluded that our patient's clinical event was consistent with SJS and that influenza B infection was the most likely cause.' The author stated, 'In our case, IVIg may have stabilized disease progression. Controlled clinical trials are needed to better support routine use of IVIg in the treatment of these disorders. Annual vaccination against influenza is recommended for individuals 6 months of age and older. 17 A history of EM, SJS, or TEN after influenza virus infection is not a specified precaution or contraindication, but patients with a similar history should be monitored closely in the post vaccination period. The lack of recurrence of SJS after influenza vaccination in our case may be of interest to providers facing a similar clinical dilemma in the future.'

Case number PHEL2016US030847, is a spontaneous report initially received from a pharmacist on 18 Nov 2016. This report refers to a 46 year old female patient (non pregnant). Medical history and concomitant medication were not reported. The patient was vaccinated with FLUVIRIN (batch number: 168701 and expiry date: 31 May 2017) in her left arm on 05 Nov 2016 at a dose of 0.5 ml, intramuscularly. On 05 Nov 2016, shortly after the patient received the vaccine, the patient began to experience a sharp pain in her left arm (sore arm) that ran down to her hand and could barely move her arm. It was reported that, the package condition was good, the doses usually stored in the original box until use and stored collected all together. When the product was removed from the refrigerator to prepare to administer, they noticed that the plunger was stiff. It was reported that, upon injection of the vaccine into the patient, she noticed that the vaccine needle had some issues entering the skin to inject into the muscle and that there was some resistance when she depressed the plunger to administered the dose, no vaccine came out of the syringe. The reporter confirmed that, the patient received the full dose of FLUVIRIN. The reporter stated that, they did not from the patient since that time and had no further updates to provide. Upon follow up with the pharmacist, pharmacist confirmed that the date of events is 5 Nov 2016 and this is the same patient (product complaint and adverse event for same patient). It was clarified that the pharmacist attempted to give first prefilled syringe that would not inject, she removed that one and injection with a different prefilled syringe. The patient called back about 2 weeks later and reported symptom of pain in her left arm that ran down to her hand. The patient states that she can barely move her arm. The outcome of the event sharp pain in her left arm (sore arm) was condition unchanged (ongoing or not recovered) and the outcome of the other events was not reported. The event sharp pain in her left arm (sore arm) was reported as non serious by the pharmacist and the seriousness of other events was not reported. The causality of the events was not reported. Follow up information received from a pharmacist on 18 Nov 2016 and 06 Feb 2017 (combined report): Added expiry date of FLUVIRIN, new event and updated reporters comment. Follow up information received from a pharmacist on 18 Nov 2016 and from Quality Assurance department (QA reference number: 1019406) on 09 Feb 2017 (combined report): Added reporter comment. SYMPTOM_TEXT: "Had her TRUMENBA and Flu shot yesterday and slept after that. She woke this AM and ate breakfast, Felt nauseated and did not eat any lunch. Presented to clinic due to numbness in her left arm from shoulder to elbow. This progressed over a couple of hours to weakness of her entire left arm. On arrival to clinic she started to have headache. Glucose was 96 and CBC and CMP are pending. She was given water and IV 1000 ml. During this time her headache escalated to pain of 10/10 and the very worst headache that she has ever had. As she continued to be disoriented and increasing headache as well as increasing weakness, she is transferred to the ED for CT scan and further work up. No fever, no diarrhea or vomiting--just nausea and unwilling to eat. Able to keep water down. Not wanting solids.
LAB_DATA: CBC, CMP, HCG, UA, toxicology screen, CT of the head, CXR  all performed 1/4/2018, all normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shortly after vaccine was administered patient exhibited symtoms of seizure-like activity then fainted. Her mother was able to catch her and helped her to lay on floor. Withins a few seconds she woke up and was able to state her name and date of birth. Within a few minutes patient was placed in sitting position in a chair and observed for several minutes. She was pale, yawning, able to speak, able to take sips of water. Blood pressure was checked at approx. 5:15pm and was 97/67 with pulse 77. At approx. 5:30pm she was able to stand and walk out of store. Contacted patient's mother by phone at approx. 7:30pm to follow up and was informed by mother she took her to local Emergency room due to continued pallor and yawning. Mother reported tests were being ran. Contacted patient's primary care physician office 1/11/18 at 1:45pm and reported incident to employee in office. She reports patient was seen in office this morning for follow up to what was reported to them as fainting due to watching her little sister receive a vaccine. Per employee, patient appears to be doing okay.

While working abroad, I was constantly exposed to smoke from tent heaters, diesel fuel, jet fuel, other petrochemical fumes, pesticides in cream and spray form, burning trash and feces and smoke from enormous oil well fires that burned constantly and blackened the skies, and on some days reduced the visibility at our position to just a few dozen feet. I was also exposed to whatever agents drifted downwind from chemical plants and other locations. One day, I was vaccinated against anthrax and other types of biological agents. On the third day, I was exposed to something that exploded in the air above our camp. Eyewitnesses reported a yellow-green chemical cloud resulting from the two explosion spread out and settled over our camp. Within minutes many of us reported burning skin, numbing of the lips and minor to extreme difficulty breathing. I was told that what we heard was just some "Sonic Booms". Late March or early April 1991, I became very ill experiencing fever like symptoms and unusual bleeding after each bowel movement until it became necessary to be taken to the nearest hospital. During the following months, my behavior patterns began to change. I became quick-tempered. This was entirely not my personality, especially the loss of control! I recall, during May 1991, I was listening to the speaker during a staff meeting. I was affected by something the speaker had said almost causing me to go into a rage. My supervisor escorted me outside of the meeting and calmed me down. Once I had returned home, I was given a new job, but I found myself often struggling to perform very simple tasks. I just couldn't comprehend what was being said to me. I often began experiencing time as being altered, and events seemed to be happening in slow motion, like an out-of-body experience, observing rather than participating in the experience. In late 1992, I began having violent outbursts usually very early in the morning, always awakening the entire family, my wife began to complain about a burning sensation during and after our sexual intercourse. My wife stated that the semen felt like a fire burning sensation. This continued to get worse until a doctor had to be seen. I began to experience loss of balance (a feeling of falling forward, sideways or backwards). I have no doubt these symptoms are the result of the exposures to a variety of hazardous substances. Presently, I remain burdened with difficulty with short-term memory, irritability and dream like states when I become distressed. I still suffer from bouts of bloody diarrhea, numbness in my finger tips, blurry vision and dizziness, some of which are unexplainable. I feel chronically disabled. I suffer from violent and irrational behavior. At times I am disoriented to the nature and circumstances of my surroundings, unable to understand my immediate actions or the consequences thereof. I have impaired ability to remember, think and reason and now faced with the process of aging in conjunction with serious disability. I can see how my stamina, strength, acuity, agility, energy and mobility slipping away. I am having trouble with my memory, especially learning new information. My day to day interactions have deteriorated.

This spontaneous case initially received on 06-Apr-2017 00:00 was reported by other non-health professional. Company suspect drug: FLUVIRIN (batch number: 1620301 and 1619701 with expiry date: 30-May-2017) (dose: 0.5 ml, unknown frequency, unknown duration, route of administration: unknown). Adverse reactions/events and outcomes: It was reported that there was a temperature excursion with FLUVIRIN product storage (characterized an Incorrect product storage) (Seriousness criteria: Non-Serious event), (Outcome-Unknown). Other non-health care professional reported that during the storage of vaccine the storage temperature reached minimum at 33.8 degrees F and maximum at 63.1 degrees F and there was a total of 6 excursions over a period of 7 days 17 hours and 10 minutes. He reported that an investigation was going on to determine whether the vaccine was given and there were no events been reported. Action taken with FLUVIRIN was not reported and outcome of the event was unknown. Reporter's Assessment: The other non-health care professional did not provide causality assessment for the event with FLUVIRIN. This case report was non-serious.

This spontaneous case was received on 09-Oct-2017, from other health professional, concerning a 25-year-old female pregnant patient with 31 weeks of pregnancy. The patient had a history of preeclampsia and 6 pregnancies and 4 miscarriages. The patient had no spontaneous abortion or still births or no contraceptives were used. The patient's son has haemophilia. The patient's current conditions included hypertension, with previous pregnancy and haemophilia carrier. The concomitant medications included labetalol, amlodipine,  DICLEGIS, UNISOM, pyridoxine, prenatal vitamins. The LMP (last menstrual period) was reported as 04-Mar-2017. On 09-Oct-2017, the patient was administered with FLUVIRIN (dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: right deltoid, batch number: 1618621, expiry date: Apr-2017). It was reported that expired FLUVIRIN was administered to the patient during 31 week of pregnancy. No adverse events occurred. The patient wanted to know whether to get revaccinated or not. The reporter assessed the report as non-serious. The EDD (estimated date of delivery) was reported as 10-Dec-2017. Significant case correction received with IRD 09-OCT-2017: Preeclampsia previously changed from current condition to historical condition and narrative was amended.
OTHER_MEDS: Labetalol; Amlodipine; Diclegis; Unisom; Pyridoxine; Prenatal vitamins
HISTORY: Pre-eclampsia; Abortion spontaneous, 4 miscarriages occurred in previous pregnancies.

This non-serious initial spontaneous case, was received from other non-health professional on 21-Sep-2017, concerning a 28-year-old adult female patient. The patient's historical vaccine included unspecified flu shot (influenza vaccine) 3 times (on unspecified date). The patient had no medical history. The patient's concomitant medications included unspecified vitamins for an unknown indication. On 20-Sep-2017, at 09:29 hrs, the patient was administered with FLUVIRIN THIOMERSAL (dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: right deltoid, batch number: expiry date: not reported). On the same day, after 5 minutes of vaccination, the patient started to feel numbness in fingers, hand, wrist and elbow. She felt a heaviness, weakness in arm and could not use both arms for driving car wheel and felt like her arm did not function. It was reported that, flu shot was more painful and patient had not experienced injection site swelling and redness. The patient did not receive any treatment for the events. It was started that, the patient got the events in the right arm. It was reported that, by the third day of vaccination the patient had no feeling of numbness. However, from then, the patient experienced small episode of localized, transient numbness, that also subsided 2 weeks post-vaccination. The patient recovered from the event numbness of upper extremities 2-weeks post vaccination. The reporter assessed the report as non-serious. Significant case correction received on 13-Oct-2017 Coding for the event feels like her arm is not functioning was changed to muscle weakness upper limb. Acute numbness in her wrists and elbows that started 5 minutes after receiving the vaccine/after 5 minutes, patient started feel numbness in fingers, then hand and wrists, up to the elbow was changed to numbness of upper extremities. Amended narrative accordingly. Follow-up report received on 26-Oct-2017: Route of administration, anatomical location was added. It was reported that, third day after vaccination the patient had no feeling of numbness. However, from then, small episode of localized, transient numbness was experienced, that also subsided 2 weeks post-vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This initial spontaneous case was received on 18-Oct-2017, from other non-health professional, concerning a 21-year-old adult female patient. The patient had a history of dairy sensitivity and was not on any concomitant medications. On 21-Nov-2011, the patient was administered with FLUVIRIN (dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, batch number: 1100401 (as reported), anatomical location, expiry date: not reported). On the same day, after receiving the vaccine, the patient developed overall allergic reaction. The patient also experienced nausea, vomiting and cramping. She was sick for 3 days. The patient also experienced stomach issues, pain and general discomfort. On 20-Oct-2017, the patient took the FLUVIRIN vaccine again and had no problems. On 24-Nov-2011, the patient had recovered from the events allergic reaction, stomach issues, pain and general discomfort and sickness. The outcome of the other events was not reported. The reporter assessed the events as non-serious. Significant follow-up received on 27-Oct-2017: It was confirmed that, no medications were taken for the events. The patient confirmed that the allergic reaction was not due to any other factor. The patient had no problems with vaccination on 20-Oct-2017. Narrative amended accordingly. Follow up received on 18-Oct-2017 from the reporter: Added events (nausea, vomiting and cramps). Amended narrative accordingly.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On January 10th in the evening about 5 hours after the vaccinations, I noticed I was itching around my neck. Just a little redness on the vaccination sites. Around 6 am in the morning of January 11, I had severe itching on my throat and around my eyes. Checking the mirror, major redness, rash on my neck and eyelids were quite swollen. Injection site on the right arm was more red. Per advice nurse, we made an appointment and as directed took an antihistamine loratadine. By the afternoon at 3:30 when I saw the Dr. the redness was more and now tonight January, 11 pm more red, hard, more sore when touched. Use hydrocortisone ointment and antihistamine as needed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2009 til present day, I began feeling dizzy, and noticed a slight imbalance in my gait. I started to get headaches, and my wife told me that I would stop breathing for a few seconds at night then I started to get sinus infections once every 6 months. 2012- yearly failed my first physical fitness exam for the run part. I took the exam again and passed it within a 6 month training time. 2013. I failed the fitness exam again. This time seeking medical assistance from my family doctor. Whom referred me to a Neurologist. 2014 - Diagnosed with Spinocerebellar Ataxia. Causing me to medically separate from the military. Early retirement.
LAB_DATA: CAT SCAN - MRI - showed the sinusitis; Blood test - showed the Spinocerebellar Ataxia
HISTORY: as of 2014 I was diagnosed with Spinocerebellar Ataxia, Sleep Apnea, And Sinusitis

SYMPTOM_TEXT: It started the morning after his shots on his left thigh with a 4-5 inch red, itchy circumference that had a fever of 104. The infection site was very large and extremely hard. His body temp. reached 101. By that evening his entire leg was swollen and red. Still with a fever of 104. He became very lethargic, slurring his words, and had a really hard time keeping his eyes open. He complained of pain all over his body and terrible stomach pains. He has been very aggressive and defiant since. He is acting like a completely different child. He has been violent and having temper tantrums, which is not him at all.
LAB_DATA: We did not take him to the doctor because I felt that they are the ones who caused this. Why take him in? We did detox baths (and still are) and natural methods to try and help him.
CUR_ILL: Upper respiratory infection a few weeks prior. The doctor said it had been enough time to vaccinate.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am a male, 5' 10" height; 172 lbs weight. Received injection with no issues. Approx 1:45PM. Felt fine until about 8:30PM when my nose starting draining and my hips and shoulders started to ache. By 9:30PM, I was shaking hard and had severe full body aches. I had to put my winter coat on with a blanket. Indoor temp was 74F. I had decided that I was getting the flu and better just get to bed. Thought I should have gotten the shot a month earlier. I had to wear a sweatshirt and pants in bed to overcome chills and shaking. Did not really sleep unitl about 2AM. Woke up at 7:45AM. Sat up on the bed and assessed my condition fully expecting that I would be laying down again. I felt as if nothing had ever happened. No chills, no shaking, no fever, no aches.
Patient was vaccinated about 3 days before conceiving, patient's mother reported a miscarriage to pharmacy that occurred about 6 weeks after receiving vaccine.
OTHER_MEDS: not aware of any, none on record at pharmacy

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderate pain left shoulder to elbow, fever 101.5, chills, nausea and vomiting, Took 2 regular ASA, but did not help pain. Ice did not help the pain. Saturday 2 days later he awoke with pain in upper left arm and other sx resolved, except for limited hearing in right ear. At 10am he took 2 caplets to decrease fever and help pain. Recommended warm compresses and monitor. On Saturday 10/2/17 patient had edema and erythema of upper left arm, deltoid area and below. Next day persistent soreness even with moist compresses. Still with limited hearing in right ear. After 3 months of complete hearing loss in right ear, hearing fully returned on 12/31/17 after ear popped.
OTHER_MEDS: Aspirin 325mg once daily, Multivitamin once daily, Fish Oil once daily

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 11-year-old female who was admitted to medical center on 1/2/18 with a sudden onset of weakness of the lower extremities. The father states that she was in her usual state of health until the morning of 1/1 at which time she complained to her father that her legs and shoulders were hurting when she was walking to the bathroom. She stated that she felt weak and was unable to walk to the bathroom without help. The father states that the rest of the day she was unable to ambulate without help because of the weakness. There was no history of pre-existing symptoms such as URI symptoms, cough, congestion, vomiting or diarrhea. No one else was sick at home either. The weakness and pain worsened so she was brought to the emergency room. There was no history of numbness or tingling associated with this. She did come from another country approximately 1-1/2 years ago and has not returned. There were no known sick contacts. She was admitted to the pediatric ICU for further management. Neurology consult was obtained who recommended an LP in addition to blood work and MRI of the head and spine. The MRIs were unremarkable as was the blood work. She was started on IVIG. They did send a respiratory virus panel which was negative. I was consulted today because she now has a fever associated with this weakness. Overnight her condition worsened requiring intubation and mechanical ventilation. There is no family history of similar type symptoms in anyone in the family. The father states that she is normally a healthy 11-year-old female attending 4th grade. Her vaccines are up-to-date according to the father. She is currently intubated and sedated. She was started on IV ceftriaxone because of fever.
Developed a fever and chills 12 hours after injection.
Mild localized reaction. No treatment needed.

On an unknown date, the patient experienced high blood pressure, heart attacks (myocardial infarction), underwent two stent placement (further not specified), and developed kidney cancer with metastasis to the ribs (renal cancer metastatic, metastases to bone). He received an unspecified chemotherapy for kidney cancer with metastasis to the ribs. Then, on an unknown date he developed transitional cell carcinoma in the bladder (bladder transitional cell carcinoma) for which the patient underwent bladder reconstruction and received more chemotherapy. On approximately 21-DEC-2017 (reported as "about 2 weeks ago") the patient developed shingles (Herpes zoster), began getting pain in his "sides and breast area, nipple pain as well as spots on his back". The patient's physician prescribed valacyclovir hydrochloride(VALTREX) on an unknown date and he began taking it on 04-JAN-2018. The outcome of all the events was unknown. Causality assessment was not provided by the reporter. Upon internal review, bladder transitional cell carcinoma, renal cancer metastatic, metastases to bone, stent placement and myocardial infarction were determined to be medically significant.
OTHER_MEDS: PLAVIX; CRESTOR; CIALIS; TOPROL XL TABLETS

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This spontaneous report as received from a nurse refers to an unspecified number of unspecified patients. The vaccines underwent temperature excursions at or above 0 to 1 degrees Celsius (also reported as 1.2 to 1.4 degrees Celsius) for 83 hours and 38 minutes and at or above -9 to 8 degrees Celsius (also reported as (-5.1 to 1.1 degrees Celsius) for 3 hours and 57 minutes, respectively. SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is the 1st time I ever had a flu shot, Dr. advised after husband had heart by-pass surgery and had us take vaccine. After a few days my right hand thumb pain to bottom joint - would lose grip without warning, items would fall out of hand. Also soreness on back of head with headache running on sides of head to front caused some nausea. After a few more days, noticed pain on bottom on right leg when going up my stairs, calf to knee. Leg would fall, had to hold on to stair rails to stabilze leg otherwise leg would just fall out from under me. Set appoint on December 7th with NP in Dr.'s office. Said could be nerves, gave me prescription Naprosyn and would follow up on 12/21/2017. Took Tests, Blood, Urine.  After taking 2 pills, pain mostly gone, went up stairs without holding rails, leg went out from under me.  Then pain started in my left thumb but not as bad as the right and had grip, and pain in bottom back, spine, then left leg from upper thigh to joint and left side top of arm. On 12/21/2017 NP told me that white cell counts elevated but not alarming. Told me I shouldn't take Flu shots, but did not think it was adversly due to flu shot. Schedule in 6 months. Did not think it was Guillian-Barre Syndrome because the patients she saw with that was hospitalized and very bad.  I had asked her about Guillian-Barre Syndrome because the pharmacist I spoke with stated I should be tested for this, and could have only mild symptons and would eventually go away. The pain in my left leg has gone, and only mild soreness on thumbs, very little back pain, but top right  thigh and joint, plus right top joint on arm pain and now some chest and top back tightness/soreness. Hopefully will go away.
LAB_DATA: 12/07/2017, ANA SCREEN W IFA W REFLEX TO TITER - Already viewed; 12/07/2017, RHEUMATOID FACTOR - Already viewed; 12/07/2017, C-REACTIVE PROTEIN - Already viewed; 12/07/2017, SEDIMENTATION RATE - Already viewed; 12/07/2017, URINALYSIS, AUTOMATED WITH MICROSCOPY - Already viewed; 12/07/2017, TSH - Already viewed; 12/07/2017, LIPID PANEL - Already viewed;  12/07/2017, HEPATIC FUNCTION PANEL - Already viewed; 12/07/2017, HEMOGLOBIN A1C - Already viewed; 12/07/2017, CBC WITH PLATELET AND DIFFERENTIAL - Already viewed; 12/07/2017, BASIC METABOLIC PANEL - Already viewed

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt. was initially given flu vaccine which he tolerated well. He was then given GARDASIL 1 dose, within 3-5 min of the shot, pt complained of "feeling weird" and weak. Later complained of throat and chest and burning. This progressed to numbness spreading from head to toe. He also described hearing echoes of his voice. This was followed by twitching of R arm and foot. Pt denied SOB, chest pain, wheezing. Pt was a little sluggish but remained oriented x 4. BP increased to 150s/90s. SpO2 98% on RA, other VS stable. Pt was taken to Hosp by EMT team (911 was called after pt started twitching). Attempt was made to contact pt but unsuccessful.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt received TDaP vaccine on 12/14/17 11:36 after screening questions indicate she had not had previous adverse reaction to this vaccine and no hx of allergy to the vaccine. Pt notifies clinic via phone call on 12/15/17 at 1536 that she was experiencing pain site of vaccine since am. States she is unable to move right arm. Offered patient follow-up appt with provider. Pt declines. Advised to use cold compress/NSAID to manage pain & to report if sx persist or worsen. Advised pt of Urgent Care hours available. 12/19/17 placed call to patient to f/u. Pt reports that is experiencing burning pain right shoulder which limits mobility of right arm. Pt has not scheduled follow-up on problem or gone to Urgent Care for re-evaluation of symptoms. Patient did have appointment with gynecologist 12/18/17 and communicated problem to provider. Provider gave Rx for NORCO to manage Rt shoulder pain. Pt states she has not taken this Rx. PCP notified. PCP places call to patient 12/19/17 and advises patient to come for exam in clinic, offered same day appt. Pt declines stating it is too difficult to get to clinic. 12/20/17 Pt comes to Urgent Care for exam reports Rt arm pain and numbness in fingertips right hand. Exam reveals no erythema, warmth or skin changes in deltoid area. Pt reported moderate to severe tenderness to palpation at mid humerus around biceps/triceps. No redness, warmth, at site of tenderness. Pt told passive ROM by provider but is unable to actively move her right arm. No evidence cellulitis. Advised to continue ice, NSAID, Alpha lipoic Acid Supp, Arnica cream, and sling. Advised to follow-up in one week. Pt received temporary handicap placard for 3 wks at her insistence. 12/26/17 Pt calls to report arm is not getting better. Appointment scheduled for f/u PCP 12/28/17. 12/26/17 pt calls to cancel appt and reschedules with another provider 01/05/18. On 01/03/15 Pt calls to report her right arm is still in pain with burning sensation and limited mobility. She cancels appt 01/05/18 stating she has not had labs drawn yet. She believes she has nerve damage related to Tdap administration 12/14/17. 01/11/18 Pt has appt with new provider and requesting referral to neurology. Full exam completed. Xray Rt shoulder ordered: negative exam. Rt shoulder/arm appearance normal. Exam notes state pt has limited ROM, full strength, 2+ reflexes, sensation to light touch. Gabapentin therapy ordered. Referrals initiated to physical therapy and neurology. Pt advised to continue ice/heat & ADVIL PRN.

Patient stated that it was showing a little red starting 30 minutes after shot but did not contact us until 2 days later. We sent patient to urgent care and they prescribed ranitidine, and certerizine for reaction. Pharmacy gave her benadryl to take 50mg dose at night and will be contacting her on Monday.
OTHER_MEDS: proair, methocarbamol, potassium omeprazole, lisinopril, furosemide, buspirone, levothyoxine, hydrocodone apap, cimzia

SYMPTOM_TEXT: PATIENT PRESENTED WITH A RED MARK UNDER HER DELTOID ANGLING TOWARDS THE BICEP ABOUT 4 INCHES BY 1 INCH AND REPORTED ITCHING ASSOCIATED WITH THE REDNESS.
Localized swelling and itching L arm at site of injection; given ZYRTEC, ibuprofen, hc cream; will continue to f/u at school clinic.

On the afternoon following the vaccine, patient noted swelling and itching of upper arm originating at site of influenza injection. Parent gave him Benadryl, swelling continued to grow; at peak arm swollen shoulder to elbow. Parent took child to Urgent Care clinic.
LAB_DATA: None. Comfort measures and antihistamines recommended in urgent care clinic. Arm swelling resolved after 3 days.
PRIOR_VAX: Same reaction to Sanofi Pasteur influenza vaccine 12/17/2014 but no reaction to Glaxo influenza vaccine 11/1/2016.  Pt did not r
ALLERGIES: egg, sesame, cashew, pistachio, walnut, pecan, and possibly other tree nuts.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: She had a fever spike to 103 about 23 hours after administration. This lasted 48 hours, but was managed with TYLENOL and MOTRIN. She also still has a small, red, painful lump at the vaccination site on her right thigh. It has been over a week since administration.
Severe pain at injection site for greater than 3 months causing shoulder to feel stiff, painful to move. Feeling of heaviness.
LAB_DATA: No testing has been done. I have completed a course of prednisone which did not improve these symptoms

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient experienced immediately swelling at time of injection, however the swelling resolved within a few minutes with no pain, redness or rash reported after follow up.
Patient has been breaking out in a rash on his upper and lower extremities.
HISTORY: heart disease, hypertension, stroke, high cholesterol

SYMPTOM_TEXT: THE PATIENT RECEIVED THE FLU SHOT AND APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES AFTER RECEIVING THE VACCINE HE BEGAN TO FEEL LIGHTHEADED. THE PATIENT STATED HE FELT DIZZY AND BEGAN TO LOOK PALE. HE WAS BROUGHT A WHEELCHAIR TO SIT IN AND AN AMBULANCE WAS CALLED. WHEN THE AMBULANCE CAME AND CHECKED HIS BLOOD PRESSURE, IT WAS 80/50. OXYGEN SATURATION WAS AT 100%. HE WAS FEELING BETTER BEFORE THE AMBULANCE TOOK HIM AWAY.
LAB_DATA: NO OTHER MEDICAL TESTS ARE KNOWN AT THIS TIME.
OTHER_MEDS: CLONAZEPAM, VISTARIL, RISPERDONE, SSRI, OTHERS ARE UNKNOWN

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Large red rash, swelling to the size of a golf ball, many small welts surrounding the area, itchy, hot to the touch, severe pain- unable to move arm or carry anything for 2 days. Ibuprofen/acetaminophen and icing the injection site offer little to no relief.
Sore upper left arm...cannot lift it, headache, muscle aches, fatigue, light sensitivity, increased glucose levels...233.
OTHER_MEDS: Aspirin, ZYRTEC, multivitamin, Vitamin E, Vitamin D
HISTORY: Diabetes, Asthma, High blood Pressure, High Cholesterol

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Persistent shoulder pain post immunization-failed NSAID, TYLENOL #3. Imaging (x-ray) WNL-referred to Ortho for steroid injection.

This report refers to a female patient of an unknown age. Medical history and concomitant medication was not reported. The patient was vaccinated with FLUVIRIN (batch number: not reported) on an unknown date. On an unknown date, the patient experienced allergy to FLUVIRIN.
