Severe headache, body aches, fatigue, hot flashes, and arm pain lasting greater than 72 hours post vaccine. Given ibuprofen which didn?t help much.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Child developed eczema on entire body, vomited, bled rectally after consuming Dairy through breastmilk. This has never happened prior to vaccine. He developed and maintained a fever almost immediately which lasted for 48 hours. He was grumpy, listless, and in pain.
ALLERGIES: After vaccine, developed life- threatening allergy to casein and all by-products.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Straight line bruise vertically down arm from injection site extending down about 3 inches. Still visible now.
Red, swollen arm that was very sensitive to the touch and hard to move.
LAB_DATA: Went to doctor and was prescribed Doxycycline Hyclate 100 MG on 1/12/2018
OTHER_MEDS: No medications taken. I am not on any.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I started having strange infrequent sharp, dull pains in my left shoulder/ upper left back area around 10:00 pm (I received the injection in my left arm). Around 12:30 my body and muscles felt very tight. Around 1:00 pm I started feeling very cold, even though the temperature in my bedroom was 73. I started shaking and shivering which lasted about 20 minutes after which time I went to sleep. I had to put two down blankets over myself and that helped me feel warmer but could not stop shivering. I had imbibed 1 1/2 glasses of wine and a rum cocktail earlier in the evening.
CUR_ILL: Had a transient global amnesia episode on 1/4/2018 that lasted for two hours. Went to emergency room all was fine on MRI and CAT scan. Also had physical exam on 1/12/2018 (where I received Shingles vaccination) and was found to be in extremely good health.
ALLERGIES: apples, pears, raw walnuts, raw hazelnuts, apricots, nectarines, kiwi, pomegranate. (slight anaphylactic reaction or itchy mouth)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After injection patient got up from chair and preceded to exit the administration area and fainted. Father at the time did have a hold of him so he did not fall. Offered to call 911 but father refused. Patient did regain conscious after a 20 seconds. Was able to respond and after a couple of minutes slowly sat him on a chair where he waited with his father until he felt well enough to walk on his own.. approx 10 to 15 minutes. During that time kept on looking in on how he was doing.
PRIOR_VAX: per father said he had gotten a little queasy on last immunization. (was told of this after child fainted)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Fever, unconsolable crying, quit talking, sick pretty much the whole time from a few hours after receiving the vaccine, still gets sick frequent with what I believe is croup(went to the er twice within 6 months of getting it for being unable to breathe due to a barking cough), still isn't talking much.
HISTORY: Since getting his 15 month vaccines, he was sick for just over a year, croupy cough pretty much consistently. Stopped verbal communication for about 10 months, still sick once or twice a month a year and a half later
PRIOR_VAX: fever of 104 after MMR 8/8/2016

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received vaccines on 01/08/2018, then on 01/09/2018 mother of patient reports that the patient woke up with a temperature of 103.3 and was unusually fussy. Upon arriving to our pediatrics office we took the patient's temperature auxiliary and it was 102.3, so we gave 1.6 ml of Ibuprofen. No other symptoms were reported by the mother, and no other symptoms were noted/reported by the doctor.
CUR_ILL: Patient's mother complains that child has hard stools

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 24 hours after receiving vaccines, he presented with runny nose, congestion, cough, and sneezing.
Patient had a hard knot on her arm after the administration of Pneumovax 23 vaccination. Patient was give an ice pack. Patient was suppose to stop by the pharmacy the next day .
A rash and hives ever since getting the vaccine if the environmental temperature is above 75 degrees Fahrenheit inside or out of doors. Cannot go outside during summer months at all.
ALLERGIES: Haldol, lamectal, thorazine, zyprexa, sudafed, aspirin, dapakote

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The baby had a low grade fever that started in the early hours of the morning the day after the vaccine. At some point one of the four vaccine sites became swollen and red. I treated with a cold compress but saw no immediate improvement yet. I considered both of those reactions to be fairly normal. Almost 24 hours after the vaccine the baby became unusually fussy and then forcefully (not quite projectile) vomited an entire feeding. As I type he's currently sleeping after the event.
PRIOR_VAX: Just the standard low fever after routine infant vaccines.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient experienced intense leg cramping and nausea after receiving FLUCELVAX. The patient stated that her symptoms were those of when she consumed eggs.
PRIOR_VAX: Patient had these symptoms when she received an egg based vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I'm sorry I don't know the specific vaccine, but it was the flu vaccine for the 2017/2018 flu season. I had the standard ache and drowsiness for 2 days following the shot. But 1 week and 2 days later, the arm pain has changed and worsened. I now have on and off muscle pain at the site of the injection. I can move my arm without issue, and I haven't been able to identify the trigger for the pain to start/stop. The pain is mild to moderate (up to a 4 out of 10 on the pain scale) and the pain seems to increase when I use my fingers for anything dexterous, like typing. At this point, I have not been able to identify anything to alleviate the pain.

Patient has malaise and general fatigue for 48 hours after dose. Patient also had significant swelling at the injection site and red-patchy rash that lasted 5 days. Patient experienced significant soreness at injection site that also lasted about 5 days.
HISTORY: blindness post shingles outbreak in the past

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient states the day after she experienced nausea and pain in the legs.

SWELLING, HARD AND SORE AT INJECTION SITE. DIARRHEA, VOMITING, SEVERE WHOLE BODY MUSCLE PAIN. WAS BEDRIDDEN FOR 4 DAYS AND TOOK A TOTAL OF 10 DAYS TO RECOVER. PATIENT STATED THE ADVERSE EVENTS STARTED WITHIN 1/2 TO 1 HOUR AFTER THE VACCINE. TOOK ALEVE FOR THE MUSCLE PAIN AND DID NOT SEEK MEDICAL HELP.
OTHER_MEDS: LEVEMIR, INVOKANA, LISINOPRIL, HYDRALAZINE, PLAVIX, CARVEDILOL, SIMVASTATIN
PRIOR_VAX: AT AGE 65, PATIENT RECEIVED PNEUMOVAX 23 WHICH SHE STATED UPSET HER STOMACH.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Knot and redness at injection sight with severe pain in arm. Warmer at injection sight than other parts of arm. Initial clinic dr told me to take ibuprofen for 5 to 7 days. It was no better. Was then prescribed malaxocam. No help. Was told it would get better with time. Symptoms continued and have lasted over 9 months. Have had tingle( pins and needles) type feeling down to my fingers for over 9 months now.  Knot at injection sight and warmth went away at 7 months but still tender in that spot. Was sent to neurologist by another doctor and had EMG. Then sent to ortho doctor. Now undergoing occupational therapy.
LAB_DATA: EMG; X-ray; Prednisone; Meloxicam; Occupational therapy

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Low grade fever for 3 days. On day three, red blotchy rash on trunk of body. Poor sleeping and general fussiness for duration.

In approximately 18 hours following the flu vaccine, my left arm ached at the site of the injection. It has now been two months since the injection, and my arm at the site of the injection still aches several times each day. I am a true believer in vaccines and have always had a flu shot. This is the first time I had the senior dose.

Was administered a flu shot at my workplace by a pharmacy employee. Two days later my left arm began to hurt. On the third day the pain extended to the shoulder and the left side of neck. I lost strength in arm and was unable to lift heavy objects as well as lift arm. Tried to alleviate the pain with ICYHOT patches but they did not work. I then visited my physician and was prescribed BEVODINIX 1 capsule every 12 hours. To date the pain has not gone away. Can lift arm and strength is back but arm still in pain when I try to lift it and cannot lift past shoulder without pain.
OTHER_MEDS: Metformin  HCL; Amlodipine Besylate; Atorvasatin Calci; Calcium/ Vitamin D

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe and excruciating pain in left arm and shoulder weakness and nerve damage and pain in left arm. Diagnosed with Parsonage Turner's Syndrome due to flu shot received on 9/27/17.
LAB_DATA: EMG; Venous Doppler; 2-xrays; 5 MRI's; Physical therapy

SYMPTOM_TEXT: He lost consciousness after the second vaccine (FLUVIRIN) I gave in the right Deltoid. For about 5 seconds while sitting in the chair. I felt his body tightening and falling forward. He did not fall but was going to slump over. Called 911 and vitals were taken. His vitals were ok and they left. He got a ride from his girlfriend.
PRIOR_VAX: He said he also fainted in middle school after a vaccine, but can't remember which one it was.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt stated injection site and area around turned blue and a big knot formed where injection was given.
OTHER_MEDS: Uloric, amlodipine, carvedilol, pataday, pravastatin, HCTZ, levothyroxine, pantoprazole

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe projectile vomiting, shaking and hands and feet turning purple. Took her to the ER, they administered Zofran and told us to ride it out basically.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe swelling (site greater than silver dollar, visibly raised from skin), redness, hard knot at vaccination site.
PRIOR_VAX: Same reaction. 30. 4/2013. Tetanus. Brand unknown.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About two weeks after the vaccination a small rash appeared on patient's leg, around the site of injection. These small blisters resolved on their own in about 3-4 days and never seemed to cause him any discomfort. Then, on December 20th, a larger, more widespread rash appeared over the left side of his chest, arm, armpit, neck, and cheek. This round of blisters/pox seemed to bother him more but also resolved on their own in about 4 or 5 days. I have photos available if they would prove useful.

Two days following administrations of PNEUMOVAX 23 vaccine, patient presented to ER with significant left arm swelling, at the site where vaccine was administered. He experienced no pain, only extreme swelling of his left arm.
Chronic constipation.

Beginning day after vaccine, patient had redness at injection site, warm painful sensations, surrounding skin felt swollen/hard to the touch. Patient did not self-treat symptoms and symptoms were persistent until day of report.
OTHER_MEDS: Methocarbamol, etodolac, gabapentin, alprazolam, amitriptyline, oxycodone

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient called pharmacy on 1/13/18 and complained of a rash after receiving 2 immunizations in the same arm on 1/10/18. He explained that the rash began on 1/11/18 in the morning and fever began in the evening  of 1/11/18. He stated he took MOTRIN for the fever and currently didn't have a fever on 1/13/18 but he had taken some MOTRIN that day. On 1/13/18 the pharmacist discussed possible adverse reactions to both immunizations and advised him how to take BENADRYL, use an ice pack, take TYLENOL, and to seek urgent care if condition worsened. On 1/13/18 he went to urgent care and they told him he had an infection. He stated that they placed him on antibiotics (generic BACTRIM DS).
LAB_DATA: pt states no medical tests or lab tests were taken pt dr just drew a circle around the red area and prescribed antibiotics on 1/13/18
OTHER_MEDS: pt reports no medications or herbals
HISTORY: pt reports no chronic health conditions

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 24 hours patient has a severe rash all over her skin. From her face to her feet. Very blotchy, red, and itchy. She also had swollen lips and eyes. We visited the ER and she received an oral steroid.
ALLERGIES: Vomiting reaction as an infant to amoxicillin Doctor cleared it to be prescribed to patient again as it is a common reaction to upset a young child's stomach. For the week she was on it this week, she was not vomiting or experiencing any other complications

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Right upper arm became red/swollen about 6x6 wide. I had fevers & chills. Right arm was hot to the touch. I went to the ER on 12/12/16 at the same facility where I received the shot. Diagnosis was cellulitis in the right shoulder where I received pneumonia shot. I was given antibiotics. From 12/8/16 to 9/2017 - I developed multiple recurring cellulitis infections in my right arm. I kept going back to the same facility where I was told it was scar tissue. In Sept 2017, I went to a different Dr who put me back on 2 types of antibiotics for a month and I was referred to an infectious disease Dr. The infectious disease Dr ordered an MRI which indicated a foreign object in my arm. I was referred to a surgeon and had surgery in December 2017 to remove the foreign object which turned out to be a cyst that had developed from the pneumonia shot.
OTHER_MEDS: PROVENTIL HFA; CALCIUM CARB/VITAMIN D; CITALOPRAM; FLUTICASONE PROPIONATE; ADVAIR; ALAWAY; CLARTIN EQ

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pain at both injection sites, but greater on left side (PPSV23) than right (Tdap) for 3 days. Hot, red area approximately 3 inches long and 2 inches wide close to PPSV23 injection site (area of injection and distal from it), painful to touch for two and a half days. Nausea, low grade fever (100F), and other flu-like symptoms for approximately 24 hours.
LAB_DATA: None. Did not visit healthcare provider as symptoms were not severe enough.
OTHER_MEDS: Zyrtec, Cymbalta, Vitamin D 2000 IU, Vitamin B complex, probiotic.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 12-15: Headache, lower back pain, nausea, swelling of right arm. 12-16: Headache, back pain, nausea, dizziness, hot/cold body symptoms, exhaustion. Approx. 6-8 size redness of injection site. Started TYLENOL and BENADRYL per Dr. orders. 12-17: still continue on TYLENOL and BENADRYL. Developed rash on face-all over-red, also rash over redness on arm of injection site. Included all of the following wk. until Dec 21, 17. I felt tired and arm took all this week at least to get the inflammation out. The sickest week I have felt in a lot of years and I am 65.

This spontaneous report was received from a pharmacist referring to a female patient of unknown age. The patient did not have any pertinent medical history, concurrent conditions, drug reaction/allergy neither was taken any concomitant medication. On 28-DEC-2017, at pharmacy, the patient was vaccinated with PNEUMOVAX23, intramuscularly, lot # N023651, expiration date on 20-MAY-2019, for pneumonia (strength and dose were not reported). On 28-DEC-2017 (also reported as 28-DEC-2019), the patient experienced facial flushing, lower back pain, erythema on both hands and complained of feeling faint. The patient sought medical attention; thus, the paramedics were called to the scene and the patient's vitals were taken. Then, she said that she felt fine. The episode lasted for 15 minutes and the pharmacist instructed the patient to take TYLENOL and to apply a heating pad to her lower back. Finally, no laboratory studies were performed. On 29-DEC-2017, at morning, the patient called the pharmacist and said that all her symptoms have resolved at an unspecified time after TYLENOL and heating pad were used. The causality assessment between the events and vaccination with PNEUMOVAX23 was not provided.

Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a female patient (age unknown). The patient's medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medication use were not provided.  On or about 23-JUL-2015 the patient was vaccinated with ZOSTAVAX, (lot# and route unknown) as recommended for routine adult health maintenance and for the prevention of shingles. The vaccine did not prevent shingles as intended, but rather caused the patient to contract a persistent strain of herpes zoster.  On or about 22-APR-2016 the patient was treated at a medical center for the onset of severe vesicular rash accompanied by a weakened immune symptoms, which was diagnosed as severe herpes zoster. The patient has been prescribed tramadol, acyclovir and trimethoprim and sulfamethoxazole (BACTRIM) for management of her painful condition. As a direct and proximate result of these malfunctions, the patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. As a further proximate result, the patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, and pain and suffering, and other damages.   Additional information has been requested.

Initial unsolicited report received from the literature on 04-Jan-2018. The following is verbatim from the article: Abstract A 2-year-old boy with influenza B infection and rapidly worsening targetoid skin lesions with mucosal involvement was diagnosed with Stevens-Johnson syndrome (SJS) and treated with oseltamivir and intravenous immunoglobulin, with resolution of illness. Subsequent quadrivalent inactivated influenza vaccine was well tolerated. This case highlights the rarity of SJS in the setting of influenza B infection and addresses the safety of administering subsequent influenza vaccines to such individuals. This case involves a 24-months-old male patient who was vaccinated with a dose of TRIVALENT INACTIVATED INFLUENZA VACCINE (Batch number, expiration date, dose, dose in series, route and site of administration were not reported) on an unspecified date (also reported as three months before presentation in the hospital). The patient was previously healthy. Other medical history was not reported. Concomitant medications were not reported. On an unknown date, after the vaccination, the patient experienced fever, congestion, rhinorrhea, myalgia and a progressive pruritic facial eruption. So on an unknown date in the winter of 2013, the patient presented in the hospital with a 5-day history of above mentioned events and was hospitalized. On an unknown date (also reported as two days before presentation in the hospital), his pediatrician had started DEXAMETHASONE, IBUPROFEN, FAMOTIDINE, and DIPHENHYDRAMINE because of suspicion of an allergic skin eruption, there were no known medication exposures, including acetaminophen or ibuprofen, preceding the appearance of skin lesions, It was reported that over the next 2 days, skin lesions became widespread, prompting reevaluation, also vital signs were significant for fever 101 degree Fahrenheit, tachycardia, and tachypnea with normal blood pressure and skin examination revealed pink, annular, edematous papules and plaques on the face, trunk, buttocks, and extremities, many with dusky, violaceous centers Multiple tense vesicles and targetoid erythematous papules were located perianally, rare serous vesicles were noted centrally, with negative Nikolsky and Asboe-Hansen signs, there was no skin tenderness. Additional findings included cervical lymphadenopathy, mildly injected sclera, and dry crusted lips. There was no genital or palmoplantar involvement. The remainder of the physical examination was unremarkable. Laboratory evaluation revealed White Blood Cells (leukocytosis) (17 x 109/L) and high C-reactive protein (10 mg/L). Empiric therapy with AZITHROMYCIN, ACICLOVIR, and CLINDAMYCIN was initiated while serologic titers and cultures (urine, skin, and blood) were pending. Because of continued fever, PIPERACILLIN/TAZOBACTAM was added on hospital day 2. A nasopharyngeal swab was positive for influenza B and negative for mycoplasma and 18 other common respiratory pathogens according to a respiratory viral polymerase chain reaction (PCR) panel. OSELTAMIVIR therapy was initiated and supportive care provided. Skin biopsy revealed necrotic keratinocytes within the epidermis and an interface dermatitis consistent with the erythema multiforme/Stevens-Johnson syndrome (EM/SJS) spectrum of inflammatory dermatoses. Immunofluorescence studies were negative for immunobullous disease. Antistreptolysin O (ASO), mycoplasma, parvovirus, herpes simplex virus (HSV), Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), and cytomegalovirus titers; surface bacterial and viral cultures; blood culture; and urine culture were negative, and acyclovir and antibiotics were subsequently discontinued. Despite supportive therapy, the patient's eruption rapidly progressed to involve more than 10 percentage of his body surface area, with skin fragility and denudation requiring transfer to intensive care. Wound care and fluid management continued, and given the progression of cutaneous disease, intravenous IMMUNOGLOBULIN (IVIg) 1 g/kg/d was administered for 3 days, resulting in defervescence and skin stabilization. His lesions reepithelialized and on an unknown date in 2013, on hospital day 7, he was discharged from the hospital. On an unknown date, after the vaccination (also reported as three months after hospital discharge), the patient developed minimal postinflammatory hypopigmentation. It was also a case of vaccination failure. It was reported that the patient was previously vaccinated for influenza at 9, 12, and 23 months of age without incident. It was also reported that during the following influenza season, after discussion with vaccine safety experts, the child received an inactivated quadrivalent influenza vaccine containing both influenza B lineages with close monitoring. He tolerated the vaccine well, without any reported adverse reaction after vaccination. Other laboratory investigations and other corrective treatment were not reported. On an unknown date, the patient recovered from influenza B virus infection, myalgia, rhinorrhea, Stevens-Johnson syndrome, erythema multiforme, fever, facial eruption, pruritus, widespread skin lesions, Skin plaque, papule, vesicles, cervical lymphadenopathy, dry crusted lips, tachycardia, tachypnea and condition aggravated (reported as the patient was well) but the outcome of minimal postinflammatory hypopigmentation was not reported. Upon internal review the event was considered as serious because of important medical event: vaccination failure. List of documents held by sender: none. Sender's Comments: Time to onset was compatible. medical history along with condition at the time of vaccination was not reported. Vaccine name and lot number was also not reported. Events are suggestive of a possible allegic response. Additional information regarding medical histiry, allergic reactions experienced in past if any should be requested. Influenza infection was diagnosed by PCR teating therefore this was also a case of vaccination failure. Additional information regarding product name or lot number should be requested. It was reported that household contact had experienced flu symptoms before current symptom onset. This could be a case of aquuired infection via contact. Based upon reported information the role fo the vaccine can not be assessed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received flu vaccine in right upper arm and immediately reports an "electric shock" sensation that traveled the length of her arm into the hand. In December, the patient went to her family doctor as symptoms continued and reports increasing weakness to the arm. Dr. reports that the nurse administering likely hit/irritated the axillary nerve during administration. He has ordered an EMG for the patient scheduled for 1/18/18.

Day after flu shot my left arm was painful. I assumed it was just sore from the injection. The following day it was still painful so I went to our Occupational Health Clinic and reported it as I was familiar with SIRVA and felt it should be reported "just in case".  I saw Dr. and told her my suspicions. She gave me steroids and had me follow up in one week. I followed up in one week with a PA with no improvement. He was not familiar with SIRVA and dismissed me just telling me to follow up with my PCP. After a few weeks of no improvement I went to my PCP and told him of my SIRVA suspicion. He just listened, but did not order anything. I also told my Neurologist, she did nothing. Months passed and the pain and my ROM got worse. I eventually complained enough my PCP ordered an EMG. The EMG confirmed slight damage from wrong injection placement, but at that point no surgical intervention needed (according to EMG). Pain has continually gotten worse and ROM poor. I contacted PCP again asking for MRI and physical therapy. I have gone to PT twice with no improvement. MRI on 1/13/2018. Shortened version of result findings: "Subtle signal variation at the articular and bursal surfaces suggest fraying/partial tearing of the tendon structures are contiguous and continuous with the full-thickness tears".  At this time I have stopped PT and am awaiting an Orthopedic Surgeon consult.
